\ie
\c 1
\s1 Procedures for burnt sacrifices
\rem /s1 Sacrifices Burned Whole; The Burnt Offering; Offerings and sacrifices; Procedures for the Burnt Offering
\p
\v 1 Yahweh¦46173 \add ≈summoned\add* Mosheh¦46171 \add (Moses¦46171)\add* to the \add ≈sacred¦46175\add* tent¦46175 and¦46172 \add ≈told him\add*,
\v 2 “Tell¦46183 the \add ≈Israelis¦46182\add* that when anyone¦46186 presents an offering¦46205 to Yahweh¦46192, it must¦46184 be presented from their \add ?own\add* herd or flock¦46201.
\v 3 If it's from the herd, it must be a bull with no¦46215 defects¦46215. It must be presented¦46223 \add ≈in front¦46226 of\add* the entrance¦46219 to the \add ≈sacred¦46221\add* tent¦46221 to be acceptable¦46225 to Yahweh¦46227.
\v 4 \add @The owner\add* must¦46229 place his hand¦46230 on the head¦46232 of that offering¦46233 to be burnt¦46233, and¦46229 then¦46229 it will be accepted¦46234 \add ≈make him right with Yahweh\add*.
\v 5 Then¦46239 he must slaughter¦46239 the \add ≈bull in front¦46244\add* of Yahweh¦46245, and the priests¦46249 (Aharon's \add (Aaron's¦46248)\add* descendants), must present¦46246 the blood and splash it all around¦46260 the altar¦46259 which¦46261 is by the entrance¦46263 of the \add ≈sacred¦46264\add* tent.
\v 6 Then¦46267 \add @the presenter\add* must¦46267 skin the \add ≈bull\add* and¦46271 cut it into pieces¦46273,
\v 7 \add ≈Meanwhile,\add* the priest¦46278 Aharon's sons must¦46275 put fire on the altar¦46282 and¦46275 arrange¦46283 wood on the fire,
\v 8 and then¦46289 \add *they\add* must¦46289 arrange¦46289 the pieces¦46294 (including¦46298 the head¦46297 and the fat portions) on top of the burning¦46307 wood on the altar¦46311.
\v 9 Then¦46313 \add @the presenter\add* must wash the innards and the feet with¦46316 water¦46316, and the priest¦46318 must \add place it\add* on¦46316 the altar¦46322, \add ≈ensuring that every¦46321 part is completely burnt¦46323 up\add* as a pleasing¦46327 aroma¦46325 for Yahweh¦46328.
\p
\v 10 “If the offering¦46344 is from the flock¦46335 (i.e., a sheep¦46339 or a goat), then it¦46347 must¦46347 be a healthy male¦46345 that's presented¦46347,
\v 11 and then¦46349 it must be slaughtered¦46349 on the northern¦46354 side of the altar facing Yahweh¦46356, and Aharon's¦46359 sons¦46358, the priests¦46360, must splash its¦46363 blood¦46363 on the altar, all around¦46367.
\v 12 Then¦46369 \add @the presenter\add* must cut it into pieces¦46371 and they must arrange¦46378 them (including¦46372 the head¦46374 and fat portions) on top of the burning¦46387 wood on the altar¦46391.
\v 13 Then¦46393 \add @the presenter¦46397\add* must wash the innards and the feet with¦46396 water¦46396, and the priest¦46398 must \add place it¦46405\add* on¦46396 the altar¦46403, \add ≈ensuring that every¦46401 part is completely burnt¦46404 up\add* as a pleasing¦46408 aroma¦46407 for Yahweh¦46409.
\p
\v 14 “\add ≈However,\add* if his burnt¦46416 offering¦46416 to Yahweh¦46418 will be a bird, then \add ≈it must¦46419 be either a dove¦46427 or a young¦46426 pigeon¦46427\add*.
\v 15 The priest¦46433 must¦46432 present¦46432 it at the altar, and then¦46432 twist its head off and burn¦46441 the head on the altar \add ≈as he\add* drains¦46443 the blood¦46444 out onto the \add ≈outer edge\add* of the altar.
\v 16 Then¦46449 he must¦46449 \add ≈pull out\add* the crop with¦46453 its contents¦46453, and¦46449 throw¦46454 it down on¦46453 the eastern¦46458 side of the altar¦46457 where the ashes¦46462 are.
\v 17 He will then¦46464 tear the bird \add mostly\add* apart¦46464 by its wings¦46466 \add ≈(but¦46464 making sure that it stays as one piece)\add*, and¦46464 \add place it\add* on¦46466 the altar¦46472, \add ≈ensuring that every part is completely burnt¦46480 up\add* as a pleasing¦46484 aroma¦46483 for Yahweh¦46485.
\c 2
\s1 Procedures for grain offerings
\rem /s1 Procedures for the Grain Offering; The Grain Offering; Grain Offerings
\p
\v 1 “When someone presents a grain¦46493 offering¦46493 to Yahweh¦46494, it must¦46491 be as fine, wheat flour¦46495 \add ≈mixed with\add* \add olive\add*, and with frankincense¦46503 added to the top of it.
\v 2 It must¦46505 be taken to the priest¦46510 Aharon's sons¦46508 who will take it \add from them\add*, then¦46505 take a handful¦46514 out, being sure to get flour¦46515, oil¦46516, and some frankincense¦46520, and \add ≈throw that memorial¦46525 portion¦46525 onto\add* the altar¦46526 to get completely burnt up as a pleasing¦46529 aroma¦46528 for Yahweh¦46530.
\v 3 Then¦46532 the rest of that grain¦46535 offering¦46535 will be for Aharon¦46536 and¦46537 his sons¦46537—it's a very sacred¦46538 part from the gifts for Yahweh¦46541.
\p
\v 4 “When someone presents something baked as their grain¦46547 offering¦46547, it must¦46545 be baked without leaven: either wheat flour mixed¦46553 with \add olive\add* oil and baked into flat buns, or else wheat flour biscuits¦46555 with \add olive\add* oil \add ≈spread on¦46554 top\add*.
\v 5 Or if your¦46567 grain¦46563 offering¦46563 is done on¦46570 the flat pan, it¦46572 must¦46572 be wheat flour¦46568 mixed¦46569 with¦46570 \add olive\add* oil¦46570 \add ≈and¦46561 made into flat biscuits\add*
\v 6 that should then be crumbled¦46574 and¦46577 have oil¦46579 poured over them as \add &your\add* grain¦46580 offering¦46580.
\v 7 Or if your¦46588 grain¦46586 offering¦46586 is \add deep-fried\add* in¦46590 a pot, it¦46591 must¦46591 be made from wheat flour¦46589 with¦46590 \add olive\add* oil¦46590.
\p
\v 8 “\add Any of the above types of\add* grain¦46596 offering¦46596 to Yahweh¦46600 must¦46593 be presented¦46601 to the priest¦46604, and¦46593 he will take¦46605 it to the altar¦46608.
\v 9 Then¦46610 he must¦46610 \add take a handful\add* as a memorial¦46617 portion¦46617 to the altar¦46619 to get completely burnt up as a pleasing¦46622 aroma¦46621 for Yahweh¦46623.
\v 10 Then¦46625 the rest of that grain¦46628 offering¦46628 will be for Aharon¦46629 and¦46630 his sons¦46630—it's a very sacred¦46631 part from the gifts for Yahweh¦46634.
\p
\v 11 “Anything that's presented¦46640 to Yahweh as a grain¦46638 offering must¦46640 not be made with any rising agent, because any leaven or honey¦46651 mustn't be burnt as a gift to Yahweh.
\v 12 \add ≈Foods¦46663 containing those\add* can be presented as a first-fruits offering, but¦46664 they¦46669 mustn't \add ≈be burnt\add* on the altar¦46666.
\v 13 \add ≈However,\add* every¦46687 grain offering must be salted—the salt in¦46677 the grain offering is a reminder of our agreement, \add ≈so it must always be present\add*.
\p
\v 14 “\add ≈Finally,\add* if you want to offer ripe grain as a grain offering to Yahweh¦46699, then it must¦46696 be a young¦46700 ear of grain that's been roasted¦46701 over the fire¦46702 and presented as a grain offering of your first¦46698 ripe grains
\v 15 \add ≈with\add* \add olive\add* oil¦46712 on it¦46717 and¦46713 some frankincense¦46715 on top. That \add also becomes\add* a grain¦46716 offering¦46716,
\v 16 and the priest¦46720 must¦46719 burn¦46719 a memorial¦46723 portion from it with some of the crushed¦46724 grains¦46724 and some of the oil¦46725 and some of the incense, \add to be burnt\add* to become smoke¦46719 as a gift to Yahweh¦46731.
\c 3
\s1 Procedures for peace offerings
\rem /s1 The Fellowship Offering; Fellowship Offerings; Offerings of Well-Being; Procedures for the Peace Offering
\p
\v 1 “\add ≈Now\add* if it's a sacrifice¦46736 for a peace¦46737 offering¦46737, if it's from the \bd herd\bd*, then either a male or female¦46750 can be presented¦46744 to Yahweh¦46754 \add ≈as long as it has no¦46751 defects¦46751\add*.
\v 2 \add @The presenter¦46761\add* must lay their hand¦46757 on the head¦46760 of the \add ≈bull or cow\add*, then¦46756 he must slaughter¦46762 it \add ≈in front of\add* the \add ≈sacred¦46764\add* tent¦46764. Then¦46756 the priest¦46769 Aharon's¦46768 sons¦46767 will splash the blood¦46772 on the altar¦46775 \add ≈on each side\add*.
\v 3 From that¦46794 peace¦46780 offering¦46781, he must¦46778 present¦46778 the fat covering¦46786 the innards and¦46778 which¦46794 is part of the innards as a gift to Yahweh¦46782,
\v 4 \add ≈along with both¦46800\add* kidneys and the fat that's attached to them, and the lobe on the liver¦46816 (all of which need to be removed¦46820 \add from the animal\add*).
\v 5 Then¦46822 Aharon's¦46826 sons¦46824 must¦46822 burn¦46822 them on the wood \add ≈that's burning¦46838\add* on the altar¦46827 as a gift—to become smoke¦46822 as a pleasing¦46841 aroma¦46840 for Yahweh¦46842.
\p
\v 6 “\add ≈However,\add* if the sacrifice¦46851 for a peace¦46852 offering¦46850 is from the \bd flock¦46849\bd*, then either a male or a female¦46856 can be presented to Yahweh¦46853 \add ≈as long as it has no¦46857 defects¦46857\add*.
\v 7 When the offering¦46868 is being presented, it must¦46869 be presented \add ≈in front¦46871\add* of Yahweh¦46872,
\v 8 and \add @the presenter¦46881\add* will put his hand¦46877 on the head¦46880 of \add the animal being\add* offered¦46881, and slaughter¦46882 it \add ≈in front¦46884\add* of the \add ≈sacred¦46885\add* tent¦46885. Then¦46874 Aharon's¦46889 sons¦46888 must¦46874 splash its blood¦46892 on the altar¦46895, \add ≈on each side\add*.
\v 9 From that¦46908 peace¦46900 offering¦46901, he must¦46898 present¦46898 the fat as a gift to Yahweh¦46902, \add ≈along with\add* the entire¦46917 fatty tail (cut off near the backbone¦46907), the fat covering¦46912 the innards and¦46898 which is part of the innards,
\v 10 \add ≈both¦46926\add* kidneys and the fat that's attached to them, and the lobe on the liver¦46942 (all of which need to be removed¦46946 \add from the animal\add*).
\v 11 Then¦46948 the priest¦46949 must¦46948 burn¦46948 them on the altar¦46950 as a food offering¦46952 made to Yahweh¦46953 by fire¦46952.
\p
\v 12 “\add ≈Similarly,\add* if the offering¦46958 is a \bd goat¦46957\bd*, then it¦46959 can be presented to Yahweh¦46961.
\v 13 \add @The presenter\add* will put his hand¦46966 on its head¦46969, and¦46963 slaughter¦46970 it \add ≈in front¦46972\add* of the \add ≈sacred¦46973\add* tent¦46973. Then¦46963 Aharon's¦46977 sons¦46976 must¦46963 splash its blood¦46980 on the altar¦46983, \add ≈on each side\add*.
\v 14 From that¦47002 peace offering¦46989, he must¦46986 present¦46986 the fat as a gift to Yahweh¦46990, \add ≈along with\add* the fat covering¦46994 the innards and¦46986 which¦47002 is part of the innards,
\v 15 \add ≈both¦47008\add* kidneys and the fat that's attached to them, and the lobe on the liver¦47024 (all of which need to be removed¦47028 \add from the animal\add*).
\v 16 Then¦47030 the priest¦47031 must¦47030 burn¦47030 them on the altar¦47032 as a food offering¦47034 made to Yahweh by fire¦47034 as a pleasing¦47036 aroma¦47035. All the fat \add ≈belongs to\add* Yahweh.
\p
\v 17 “\add This\add* regulation¦47042 must be permanent for \add all\add* \add ≈future\add* generations¦47044: All of you must \add ≈never\add* eat¦47054 fat or blood¦47052.”
\c 4
\s1 Procedures for sin offerings
\rem /s1 Procedures for the Sin Offering; Offerings for Unintentional Sins; Sin Offerings; The Sin Offering
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh¦47058 told Mosheh¦47061 \add (Moses¦47061)\add*,
\v 2 “Tell the \add ≈Israelis¦47067\add* that if a person \add ≈breaks\add* any of Yahweh's regulations unintentionally¦47075, or does anything that he said shouldn't¦47080 be done, \add then this is the procedure:\add*
\p
\v 3 “If it's \bd the \+add ≈high\+add* priest¦47087\bd* \add ≈who's done it\add*, \add that¦47095 causes\add* the \add ≈nation\add* to be guilty¦47090, and for his¦47094 transgression he must¦47089 present¦47092 a bull¦47097 \add ≈with no¦47101 defects¦47101\add* to Yahweh¦47102 as a sin offering¦47092.
\v 4 He must bring¦47105 the bull before Yahweh at the entrance¦47111 of the \add ≈sacred¦47112\add* tent, then¦47105 he must place his hand on \add *its\add* head and¦47105 slaughter¦47124 \add *it\add* \add ≈in front¦47114\add* of Yahweh.
\v 5 Then¦47131 the \add ≈high\add* priest¦47132 must¦47131 get some of the bull's¦47135 blood¦47134 and¦47131 bringing¦47136 it into the \add ≈sacred¦47140\add* tent¦47140,
\v 6 he must dip his finger¦47147 into \add *it\add* and¦47143 seven¦47153 times¦47154 he must \add ≈flick\add* the blood \add ≈towards\add* the \add ≈front\add* of the curtain¦47160 of the sanctuary¦47161 \add ≈in¦47148 front\add* of Yahweh¦47156.
\v 7 Then the \add high\add* priest¦47164 must put some of the blood on¦47177 the \add four\add* \add ≈projecting corners\add* of the incense altar (\add ≈located\add* inside the sacred tent \add ≈in¦47177 front¦47174\add* of Yahweh¦47175 \add and\add* used for \add burning\add* fragrant¦47173 incense). Then \add he must go back outside and\add* pour \add ≈the rest\add* of the bull's¦47184 blood out at the base of the altar for burnt¦47190 offerings¦47190 (which is \add out\add* at the entrance¦47193 to the \add ≈sacred\add* tent).
\v 8 Then¦47197 \add @the high priest\add* must¦47204 \add ≈remove\add* all the fat from the bull¦47202 being offered as a sin¦47203 offering¦47203, \add including¦47213\add* the fat covering¦47209 the innards and¦47213 which¦47217 is a part of the innards,
\v 9 \add ≈both¦47223\add* kidneys and the fat that's attached to them, and the lobe on the liver¦47239 (all of which need to be removed¦47243 \add from the animal\add*)
\v 10 just \add ≈like you'd do\add* for the bull¦47247 of the peace¦47249 offering. Then the priest¦47251 must¦47250 burn¦47250 them on the altar¦47253 for the burnt¦47254 offering.
\v 11 \add ≈However,\add* the bull's hide¦47258 and its meat¦47264, plus¦47260 it's head¦47267 and feet, and innards and dung,
\v 12 must be taken outside¦47282 the camp¦47283 to the clean place¦47286 where they pour out the ashes, and they must \add make\add* a fire¦47297 with¦47297 wood there on¦47297 top of the ashes and burn¦47292 it there.
\p
\v 13 “If¦47309 it's the \bd whole community\bd* that \add unintentionally\add* transgresses by doing something that Yahweh¦47320 prohibited, then they'll be guilty¦47325 even if the community didn't¦47322 \add actually\add* notice¦47313.\x + \xo 4:13-21: \xt Num 15:22-26.\x*
\v 14 \add ≈When¦47327\add* they become aware of \add ≈what they've done wrong\add*, then¦47327 the community must¦47327 present¦47332 a \add ≈young¦47335\add* bull¦47334 \add ≈in front¦47341\add* of the \add ≈sacred¦47342\add* tent as a sin offering¦47332.
\v 15 Then¦47345 the community¦47347 elders¦47346 must¦47345 place their¦47350 hands¦47350 of the bull's¦47354 head¦47353 \add ≈in front¦47355\add* of Yahweh¦47356, and¦47357 slaughter¦47357 \add *it there\add*.
\v 16 The \add ≈high\add* priest¦47365 must¦47364 take some of the bull's¦47368 blood¦47367 into the \add ≈sacred¦47371\add* tent¦47371
\v 17 and seven¦47381 times¦47382 \add *he\add* must¦47374 dip his finger¦47376 in it and \add ≈flick\add* the blood¦47379 \add ≈towards\add* the \add ≈front\add* of the curtain¦47387 of the sanctuary \add ≈in front\add* of Yahweh¦47384.
\v 18 Then he must put some of the blood on¦47402 the \add four\add* \add ≈projecting corners\add* of the \add incense\add* altar (\add ≈located\add* inside the sacred tent \add ≈in¦47402 front¦47399\add* of Yahweh¦47400). Then \add he must go back outside and¦47389\add* pour \add ≈the rest of\add* the bull's blood out at the base of the altar for burnt¦47413 offerings¦47413 (which is \add out\add* at the entrance¦47416 to the \add ≈sacred\add* tent).
\v 19 Then¦47420 he must¦47424 \add ≈remove\add* all the fat from \add @the slaughtered bull\add* and¦47420 burn¦47426 up \add @that fat\add* on the altar¦47427,
\v 20 and he should process the bull just the same as for a sin offering¦47434. Then¦47429 the priest¦47441 \add ≈will have made them right with God\add* and they'll be forgiven¦47442.
\v 21 Then¦47445 he must¦47445 take \add the remaining parts of\add* the bull outside¦47451 the camp and burn it \add ≈as described above\add* \add and\add* it will be the sin offering¦47460 for the community.
\p
\v 22 “If it's \bd a leader¦47466\bd* that \add unintentionally¦47479\add* transgresses by doing something that his god¦47474 Yahweh¦47473 prohibited, then he'll be guilty¦47480.
\v 23 \add Alternatively, maybe someone else will point out his failing\add* to him. Then he must¦47490 bring¦47490 an offering¦47493 of a male goat¦47494 \add ≈with¦47489 no¦47497 defects¦47497\add*.
\v 24 He must¦47499 place his hand¦47500 on¦47507 \add *its\add* head¦47503 and¦47499 slaughter it in¦47507 the place where¦47508 \add the animals for\add* the burnt¦47513 offering are slaughtered. It will be a sin offering,
\v 25 and the priest¦47520 must¦47519 take some of the blood of that sin offering and with¦47523 his finger¦47523, put some of the blood on¦47523 the \add four\add* \add ≈projecting corners\add* of the altar for burnt offerings.
\v 26 He must¦47545 burn up all the fat on the altar¦47546 just like the fat from the peace¦47549 offering¦47549, and \add that way\add*, the priest¦47552 will make \add @that leader\add* \add ≈right with God\add* and he'll be forgiven¦47554.
\p
\v 27 “If it's \bd an \+add ordinary\+add* person¦47560\bd* who \add unintentionally¦47563\add* transgresses by doing¦47566 something that¦47570 Yahweh¦47569 prohibited, then they'll be guilty¦47574.\x + \xo 4:27-31: \xt Num 15:27-28.\x*
\v 28 \add Alternatively, maybe someone else will point out their failing\add* to them. Then due to their transgression, \add @that person\add* must¦47582 bring¦47582 an offering¦47583 of a female goat¦47584 \add ≈with no¦47586 defects¦47586\add*.
\v 29 He must¦47594 place his hand¦47597 on¦47605 the head¦47599 of the \add goat that's a\add* sin offering, and¦47594 slaughter¦47601 \add *it\add* at¦47605 the place for burnt¦47606 offerings.
\v 30 Then¦47608 the priest¦47609 must¦47608 take some of the blood \add and\add* with¦47611 his finger¦47611, put some of the blood on¦47611 the \add four\add* \add ≈projecting corners\add* of the altar for burnt¦47617 offerings¦47617, and then¦47608 pour \add the rest of\add* the blood at¦47611 the altar's base.
\v 31 Then¦47629 \add @the presenter\add* must¦47634 pull out all the fat (just like it's done for the peace¦47640 offering¦47640), and the priest will \add ≈burn¦47641\add* it on the altar¦47643 to make a pleasing¦47645 aroma¦47644 for Yahweh¦47646, and to \add ≈make that person right with God\add*, and they'll be forgiven¦47650.
\p
\v 32 “\add ≈But¦47654\add* if it's a lamb¦47656 that \add @the individual\add* wants to bring as their sin¦47659 offering¦47659, then it must¦47657 be a female¦47660 \add ≈with no¦47661 defects¦47661\add*.
\v 33 \add @The presenter\add* must¦47664 put their hand¦47667 on¦47674 the head¦47669 of the \add ≈lamb\add* and¦47664 slaughter it as a sin offering at¦47674 the place¦47674 where¦47675 burnt¦47679 offerings are slaughtered.
\v 34 Then¦47681 the priest¦47682 must¦47681 take some of the blood \add and\add* with¦47685 his finger¦47685, put some of the blood on¦47685 the \add four\add* \add ≈projecting corners\add* of the altar for burnt¦47691 offerings, and then¦47681 pour \add the rest of\add* the blood at¦47685 the altar's base.
\v 35 Then¦47703 \add @the presenter\add* must¦47708 pull out all the fat (just like it's done for the peace¦47715 offering¦47721), and the priest will \add ≈burn¦47716\add* it on the altar¦47719 to make a pleasing aroma for Yahweh¦47722, and to \add ≈make that¦47729 person right with God\add*, and they'll be forgiven¦47732.
\c 5
\s1 More needs for sin offerings
\rem /s1 Cases Requiring Sin Offerings; Sins Requiring a Sin Offering
\p
\v 1 “If someone is a witness¦47744 to a case \add ≈because of something they saw¦47746 or knew¦47748 about\add*, and hears¦47740 an oath \add in court\add* but¦47736 doesn't \add ≈testify\add*, then they'll \add ≈become guilty¦47754\add*.
\p
\v 2 “If someone touches¦47759 anything ‘unclean’ (e.g., a dead domestic or wild animal¦47766, or some creature) \add ≈without realising it\add*, they \add still\add* become ‘unclean’ and is guilty¦47781.
\p
\v 3 “If someone touches¦47785 anything ‘unclean¦47791’ from \add another\add* person, even if they \add initially\add* \add ≈didn't realise what it was\add*, they become guilty¦47797.
\p
\v 4 “If someone makes a rash promise, whether it's to do something good¦47808 or something bad, and even if they were \add just\add* speaking¦47811 carelessly but¦47814 find out \add later\add*, they become guilty¦47819.
\p
\v 5 “\add ≈So¦47823 then¦47823\add* \add @the person\add* that became guilty¦47826 from any of the above, must¦47826 confess¦47829 their wrongdoing
\v 6 and present a penalty¦47837 to Yahweh¦47838 to address that¦47841 wrongdoing, and must¦47834 present a female lamb¦47847 or young goat¦47850 as a sin offering¦47852, and the priest¦47855 will \add act on their behalf\add* \add ≈to make them right with God\add*.
\p
\v 7 “\add ≈However if that¦47870 person can't¦47860 afford\add* a sheep¦47865, then¦47858 for their guilt¦47869 offering because of \add ≈their transgression\add*, they must¦47861 bring¦47866 two doves or \add ≈young¦47877\add* pigeons to Yahweh¦47880—one for a sin¦47882 offering and¦47858 one for a burnt¦47884 offering.
\v 8 \add @The presenter\add* must¦47886 take them to the priest¦47890 who will present the sin¦47895 offering¦47891 first¦47896—twisting \add @the bird's\add* head¦47900 off from the neck, \add ≈but¦47886\add* not \add ≈pulling\add* the body \add in half\add*.
\v 9 Then¦47906 he must¦47906 sprinkle¦47906 some of the blood from that sin offering onto the side of the altar, and¦47906 then¦47906 drain¦47915 out the rest of the blood at¦47914 the altar's base. That will be the sin offering.
\v 10 The second¦47925 \add >bird\add* will be for a burnt¦47927 offering¦47926 as per the regulation¦47928. The priest¦47931 will make \add @the presenter\add* \add ≈right with God\add* after their wrongdoing, and¦47923 they'll be forgiven¦47936.
\p
\v 11 “\add ≈However if that¦47956 person still can't¦47942 afford\add* those two doves or \add ≈young¦47949\add* pigeons, then they can present¦47955 a kilogram of fine wheat flour¦47960 for a sin offering. It mustn't have oil¦47966 or frankincense¦47971 in it because it's a sin offering.
\v 12 \add @The presenter\add* must¦47976 take it to the priest who will then¦47976 take a handful of it, and¦47976 burn¦47989 that memorial¦47988 portion¦47988 on the altar¦47990 for burnt offerings¦47992 to Yahweh¦47993. That will be the sin¦47994 offering.
\v 13 The priest will make \add @the presenter\add* \add ≈right with God\add* after their wrongdoing as per one of the above, and¦47997 they'll be forgiven¦48008. \add The rest of\add* \add @the flour\add* will be for the priest, similar to a grain¦48012 offering¦48012.”
\s1 More on guilt offerings
\rem /s1 Repayment Offerings; The Guilt Offering; Procedures for the Guilt Offering; Offerings with Restitution
\p
\v 14 Then Yahweh¦48016 told Mosheh¦48019 \add (Moses¦48019)\add*,
\v 15 “If¦48035 someone acts unfaithfully¦48025 \add ≈but¦48027\add* unintentionally¦48028 \add ≈desecrates something that's sacred¦48029\add* to Yahweh¦48030, then because of their guilt, \add @that person\add* must¦48025 present ram \add ≈with¦48028 no¦48037 defects¦48037\add* from the flock¦48040, or silver¦48042 \add ≈coins using the official valuation¦48041\add*, as a guilt offering.
\v 16 They must also compensate for the sacred¦48055 item, but¦48050 with an extra twenty percent. That must all be given to the priest who will make \add @the presenter\add* \add ≈right with God\add* with that¦48051 ram as the guilt¦48069 offering¦48069, and¦48050 they'll be forgiven¦48070.
\p
\v 17 “If someone transgresses by violating¦48079 \add even\add* one of Yahweh's \add ≈regulations or prohibitions\add*, even if they didn't¦48086 realise it¦48078, they become guilty and must¦48078 bear responsibility for that¦48085 guilt.
\v 18 Then¦48095 \add @that person\add* must¦48095 take a ram from the flock¦48100 that \add ≈has no¦48097 defects¦48097\add* to the priest for a guilt¦48102 offering¦48102. Then the priest will make \add @the presenter\add* \add ≈right with¦48101 God\add* after that transgression (even if they weren't aware of it), and¦48095 they'll be forgiven¦48118.
\v 19 That's a guilt offering¦48121, because they were clearly guilty before Yahweh¦48125.”
\c 6
\rem /s1 Sins Requiring a Guilt Offering
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh¦48271 told Mosheh¦48274 \add (Moses¦48274)\add*,\x + \xo 6:1-7: \xt Num 5:5-8.\x*
\v 2 “Someone who transgresses against Yahweh by \add ≈cheating\add* with respect to a deposit or a pledge, or by theft or extortion,
\v 3 or by finding lost property and then denying it¦48324, or making an oath that was knowingly false, or by any other typical transgression that people do,
\v 4 then they've become guilty as a result of that transgression. \add @That person\add* must¦48337 return what was stolen or extorted, or \add ≡return\add* the deposit or the lost property,
\v 5 or \add ≈make amends for a false oath\add*. They must¦48362 return the full value plus¦48358 an extra twenty percent \add ≈as soon as the guilt is discovered\add*.
\v 6 Then \add @that person\add* must¦48384 take a ram from the flock \add ≈with no defects\add* to the priest as a guilt offering to Yahweh,
\v 7 and the priest will make \add @the presenter¦48397\add* \add ≈right with Yahweh¦48403\add* after whatever that transgression was to make them guilty, and they'll be forgiven.
\s1 The fire and the ashes
\rem /s1 Further Instructions for the Burnt Offering; Sacrifices Burned Whole; The Burnt Offering; Instructions concerning Sacrifices
\p
\v 8 Then Yahweh¦48429 told Mosheh,
\v 9 “Tell Aharon \add (Aaron¦48435)\add* and his sons¦48436 that these are the \add #regulations\add* for the burnt \add #offerings\add*: The burnt offering must remain¦48432 on the altar's hearth, on the altar all night until the morning and the fire \add ≈must be kept burning\add* on it.
\v 10 Then¦48452 the priest must¦48449 \add ≈put on\add* his linen underwear and linen robe and \add ≈remove\add* the fatty ashes from the burnt \add #offerings\add* on the altar, and pile them beside \add *it\add*.
\v 11 \add ≈After that\add*, he'll \add ≈get changed again into his regular\add* clothes and take \add &those\add* ashes outside the camp to a ‘clean’ place.
\v 12 \add ≈Meanwhile,\add* the fire on the altar must be kept burning—it must never go out. Every morning the priest must put more wood on the fire, then he must arrange more offerings on the fire—he should burn the fat of the fellowship offerings on that fire so the smoke rises.
\v 13 \add Yes,\add* the fire must¦48497 burn continually¦48506 on¦48508 the altar—never going out.
\s1 Procedures for the grain offering
\rem /s1 Further Instructions for the Grain Offering; The Grain Offering; Grain Offerings
\p
\v 14 “Here's the regulations for the grain¦48521 offering¦48521: Aharon's sons must¦48517 present¦48523 it \add ≈before\add* Yahweh¦48527 \add ≈in¦48516 front\add* of the altar.
\v 15 \add @The priest¦48530\add* must¦48534 take a handful of the flour from that grain offering¦48534, being sure it includes some of the oil and the incense, and burn it on the altar as a memorial portion¦48536 to become a pleasing aroma for Yahweh¦48539.
\v 16 The remainder \add of that flour\add* will be \add ≈used as food\add* for Aharon and¦48544 his sons—they must¦48549 eat the flat bread in a sacred place, i.e., in the courtyard of the \add ≈sacred\add* tent.
\v 17 It must not be baked with any rising agent. I give that to them from \add ≈what's given to me\add*. It's \add ≈very\add* sacred just like the sin offering and¦48555 the guilt offering.
\v 18 Any of Aharon's male descendants can eat it—it'll be their portion from Yahweh's gifts throughout the generations. Anyone who touches \add @Yahweh's gifts\add* will become sacred¦48582 \add themself\add*.”
\s1 Procedures for the ordination offering
\rem /s1 Procedures for the Ordination Offering
\p
\v 19 Then Yahweh told Mosheh,
\v 20 “On the day when one of Aharon's male descendants is consecrated as a priest, this is what he must¦48602 present to Yahweh: a continual grain offering of a kilogram of fine wheat flour—half for the morning and half for the evening.
\v 21 It must be mixed with \add olive\add* oil then cooked with oil on¦48629 a flat pan. It must then be broken¦48626 into pieces and presented as a grain offering to make a pleasing aroma for Yahweh.
\v 22 The priest who's next in¦48640 line to become \add ≈high\add* priest must offer it and it must be completely burnt for Yahweh. This is a permanent regulation.
\v 23 Any grain offering¦48650 by a priest must be completely burnt¦48663—it must not be eaten¦48661.”
\s1 Procedures for the sin offering
\rem /s1 Sin Offerings; Further Instructions for the Sin Offering; The Sin Offering
\p
\v 24 Then Yahweh told Mosheh,
\v 25 “Tell Aharon and his sons that these are the \add #regulations\add* for the sin \add #offerings\add*: The sin offering must be slaughtered \add ≈in front\add* of Yahweh at the place where the burnt \add #offerings\add* are slaughtered. It's a \add ≈very\add* sacred \add activity\add*.
\v 26 The priest who offers the sin offering \add ≈must be the one to eat it\add*. It must be eaten in a sacred place, i.e., in the courtyard of the \add ≈sacred\add* tent.
\v 27 Everything that touches the \add animal's\add* body will become sacred. Anyone who \add ≈gets the blood on their\add* clothes, must wash them in a sacred place.
\v 28 Any clay pot that it's been boiled in, must then be shattered, but if it's boiled in a bronze pot, then that must be scoured and rinsed with water.
\v 29 Any male in the priests' \add families\add* may eat it—it's \add ≈very\add* sacred.
\v 30 \add ≈However,\add* every sin offering that has its blood taken inside the \add ≈sacred\add* tent to make \add ≈someone right with God\add*, then that \add meat\add* mustn't be eaten—it must be completely burnt up.
\c 7
\s1 Procedures for the guilt offering
\rem /s1 Repayment Offerings; The Guilt Offering; Further Instructions for the Guilt Offering
\p
\v 1 “Then these are the \add #regulations\add* for the \add ≈very\add* sacred¦48669 guilt¦48668 \add #offerings\add*:
\v 2 The guilt¦48682 offering must be slaughtered at the same place¦48673 as the burnt¦48678 \add #offerings\add*, and¦48683 the blood¦48685 must be splashed on \add ≈each side of\add* the altar¦48689.
\v 3 \add @The presenter\add* must¦48696 present all the fat \add including¦48700\add* the fatty tail, the fat covering¦48703 the innards,
\v 4 \add ≈both¦48709\add* kidneys and the fat that's attached to them, and the lobe on the liver¦48725 (\add ≈all of which\add* need to be removed¦48729 \add from the animal\add*).
\v 5 Then¦48731 the priest¦48733 must¦48731 burn¦48731 those on the altar¦48734 as a guilt¦48737 offering to Yahweh¦48736.
\v 6 Any male¦48742 in¦48743 the priests' \add families\add* may eat¦48744 it—it's \add ≈very\add* sacred¦48746.
\v 7 The regulations are the same for the guilt offering as for the sin¦48752 offering—the priest¦48757 who \add ≈offers the guilt offering\add* \add ≈must¦48759 be the one to eat it\add*.
\p
\v 8 “Whenever a priest presents someone's burnt offering, the skin¦48771 of the animal that was presented belongs¦48777 to that priest.
\v 9 Any grain¦48781 offering¦48781 that's baked¦48783 in an oven, or cooked in a pan or on¦48784 a griddle, will belong¦48796 to the priest¦48792 who presents¦48793 it.
\v 10 Any grain¦48800 offering¦48800 that's either dry or mixed¦48801 with¦48803 oil¦48803, belongs¦48809 to all of Aharon's male descendants \add ≈without any distinction\add*.
\s1 Procedures for the peace offering
\rem /s1 The Fellowship Offering; Further Instructions; Fellowship Offerings; Further Instructions for the Peace Offering
\p
\v 11 “Then these are the \add #regulations\add* for sacrificing¦48816 peace¦48817 offerings¦48817 to present¦48819 to Yahweh¦48820:
\v 12 If it's presented \add ≈from thankfulness\add*, then the sacrifice¦48831 \add ≈must¦48826 be accompanied by\add* thanksgiving flat bread buns (\add made from flour\add* mixed with \add olive\add* oil), and flat biscuits¦48837 smeared¦48839 with oil, and buns \add made from\add* fine wheat flour mixed with oil,
\v 13 \add ≈plus\add* risen bread¦48850 rolls. \add All that\add* must¦48852 accompany the peace¦48858 offering¦48853 \add ≈from thankfulness¦48857\add*.
\v 14 Then¦48860 he must¦48860 present one of each \add kind of bread\add* as a contribution¦48866 to Yahweh¦48867. Those will belong¦48875 to the priest¦48868 who splashes the blood¦48872 for the peace¦48873 offerings¦48873.
\v 15 The meat of the thankfulness¦48879 sacrifice¦48878 of those peace¦48880 offerings¦48880 must¦48883 be eaten¦48883 the \add ≈same day¦48881 that it's offered—none of can be left\add* until¦48888 morning¦48890.
\v 16 \add ≈However,\add* if the sacrificed offering is a vow or freewill¦48897 offering, then¦48892 it can be eaten that same day and¦48892 \add also\add* the next day,
\v 17 \add ≈but¦48911\add* any left-over meat must¦48917 be burnt¦48917 up on the fire¦48916 on the third¦48915 day¦48914.
\v 18 If any of that meat from the sacrifice¦48924 was eaten on the third¦48927 day¦48926, the presenter¦48930 won't be accepted¦48929 and \add ≈they won't be forgiven\add*. It is spoilt, and anyone¦48930 who eats¦48938 any of it will bear their own \add ≈guilt\add*.
\v 19 If any meat touches¦48946 anything that's ‘unclean¦48949’, then¦48943 it must not be eaten—it must be burnt¦48953 up in¦48952 the fire¦48952. \add ≈However,\add* any long as the meat remains ‘clean’, it can be eaten by any person who's ‘clean’.
\v 20 If¦48969 a person who was ‘unclean¦48970’ were to eat any of the meat from the sacrifice¦48966 for a peace¦48967 offering¦48967, then¦48961 that¦48968 \add >person\add* must¦48964 be cut off from \add ≈the community\add*.
\v 21 \add ≈Similarly,\add* when a person touches¦48980 anything ‘unclean’ (e.g., human¦48985 uncleanness, or an unclean animal¦48988, or a detestable¦48993 creature¦49003), and¦48977 then¦48977 they eat some of the meat of the sacrifice¦48998 for a peace¦48999 offering¦48999 that \add now\add* belongs to Yahweh¦49001, that \add >person\add* must¦48980 be cut off from \add ≈the community\add*.
\s1 Don't eat fat or blood
\rem /s1 Eating Fat and Blood Forbidden; The Forbidden Blood and Fat
\p
\v 22 Then Yahweh¦49009 told Mosheh¦49012,
\v 23 “Tell¦49019 the \add ≈Israelis¦49018\add* that you all must not eat¦49028 the fat from \add #cattle or sheep¦49025 or goats\add*,
\v 24 ⇔plus you all definitely must¦49034 not eat the fat from an animal \add ≈that died naturally or was killed by wild animals although you can use it for other purposes\add*.
\v 25 Anyone¦49045 who does eat the fat from an animal presented¦49051 as a gift to Yahweh¦49054 must¦49051 be cut off from \add ≈the community\add*.
\p
\v 26 “\add ≈Also,\add* you all must not eat¦49064 blood¦49062 from either a bird or an animal¦49068, \add ≈no matter where you're living¦49066\add*.\x + \xo 7:26-27: \xt Gen 9:4; Lev 17:10-14; 19:26; Deu 12:16,23; 15:23.\x*
\v 27 Any person¦49072 who does eat¦49075 blood¦49078 must¦49075 be cut off from \add ≈the community\add*.”
\s1 The priests' portions
\rem /s1 The Priests' Share; A Portion for the Priests
\p
\v 28 Then Yahweh¦49086 told Mosheh¦49089,
\v 29 “Tell the \add ≈Israelis¦49095\add* that anyone¦49098 who offers a peace offering to Yahweh must¦49104 take \add ≈some of it as\add* his peace offering to Yahweh.
\v 30 They must¦49113 \add ≈personally carry\add* Yahweh's gift \add which will be\add* the breast with its fat and raise it \add ≈in front¦49129\add* of Yahweh as a wave offering¦49115,
\v 31 and the priest¦49133 must¦49132 burn¦49132 that fat up on the altar¦49137 \add ≈but¦49132\add* the breast¦49139 will be for Aharon¦49140 and his sons¦49141.
\v 32 The right¦49145 thigh¦49144 from the sacrifices¦49149 of your peace¦49150 offerings¦49150 must¦49146 be given to the priest¦49148—
\v 33 whichever \add ≈priest (Aharon's¦49161 descendant) who handled\add* the blood¦49155 of the peace¦49156 offerings¦49152 and¦49157 the fat, that right¦49165 thigh¦49164 will be his portion¦49166
\v 34 because I took the breast¦49171 from the wave offering and the thigh¦49175 from the contribution¦49176 of the \add ≈Israelis'\add* peace¦49183 offerings¦49183, and I gave¦49184 them to Aharon the priest¦49187 and his sons as an ongoing portion¦49189 from the \add ≈Israeli¦49179 people\add*.
\v 35 That's the share¦49197 for Aharon and¦49199 his sons¦49200 from the gifts to Yahweh since Mosheh presented¦49204 them to Yahweh as priests¦49206.
\v 36 Yahweh¦49211 commanded¦49210 them to be given¦49212 to them \add back\add* on the day¦49214 when he anointed¦49215 them out of all the \add ≈Israeli¦49218 people¦49218\add* \add and made it\add* a permanent regulation for \add future\add* generations¦49222.
\p
\v 37 \add #Those are the regulations\add* for the burnt¦49226 \add #offerings\add*, the grain¦49227 \add #offerings\add*, the sin¦49228 \add #offerings\add*, the guilt¦49229 \add #offerings\add*, the ordination¦49230 \add #offerings\add*, and the peace¦49232 \add #offerings\add*
\v 38 that Yahweh \add ≈gave to\add* Mosheh¦49239 at¦49240 Mt¦49240. Sinai on¦49240 the day¦49242 when he ordered¦49235 the \add ≈Israelis¦49246\add* to present¦49248 their¦49251 offerings¦49251 to Yahweh \add when they were there\add* in¦49240 the Sinai wilderness¦49253.
\c 8
\s1 Ordination of Aharon and his sons
\rem /s1 The Rites of Ordination; Ordination of the Priests; The priesthood; The Ordination of Aaron and His Sons
\r (Exo. 29:1-37)
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh¦49258 told Mosheh¦49261 \add (Moses¦49261)\add*,
\v 2 “Take Aharon \add (Aaron¦49267)\add* and his sons¦49270 with their clothes¦49273 and the anointing¦49276 oil¦49275, and the bull¦49279 for the sin¦49280 offering¦49280 and two¦49282 rams, and a basket¦49285 of unleavened¦49286 bread¦49286,
\v 3 and¦49288 assemble¦49292 the entire¦49289 \add ≈community\add* at the entrance¦49295 to the \add ≈sacred¦49296\add* tent¦49296.”
\p
\v 4 \add ≈So¦49299\add* Mosheh¦49300 did exactly has Yahweh¦49303 had commanded¦49302 him, and¦49305 the \add ≈people\add* assembled¦49305 at the entrance¦49309 of the \add ≈sacred¦49310\add* tent¦49310.
\v 5 Then¦49313 Mosheh¦49314 told the \add ≈assembled people\add*, “This \add ceremony\add* is what Yahweh¦49323 has told us to do.”
\p
\v 6 Then¦49326 Mosheh¦49327 presented¦49326 Aharon¦49330 and his sons¦49333 and \add after\add* washing them with water¦49336,
\v 7 he put the tunic¦49342 on \add @Aharon\add* and wrapped the sash¦49345 \add around\add* him, and then¦49338 put the robe¦49350 on him. Then¦49338 he put the sacred apron on him, tying \add *its\add* finely woven waistband to fasten it onto him.
\v 8 Then¦49364 he \add ≈attached\add* the chest pouch and put the Urim and Tummim into the pouch.
\v 9 \add ≈Finally\add* he placed the turban on his head¦49386, and¦49380 fastened the golden¦49397 flower-shaped plate¦49396 (that sacred¦49399 crown¦49398 that demonstrates that Aharon is set apart to only serve Yahweh) to the front¦49393 of the turban, exactly as Yahweh had instructed¦49401 Mosheh¦49405.
\p
\v 10 Then¦49407 Mosheh¦49408 took¦49407 the anointing oil¦49411 and anointed \add &Yahweh's\add* residence and everything in it, thus consecrating¦49424 \add ≈it all\add*.
\v 11 Seven times¦49433 he flicked some of it onto the altar—anointing¦49434 the altar and all its utensils¦49442 and the basin and its base, thus consecrating them.
\v 12 He poured¦49451 some of the anointing oil¦49452 over Aharon's head¦49455, thus anointing him to consecrate him.
\v 13 Then¦49461 Mosheh presented¦49461 Aharon's sons¦49465 and dressed them in tunics¦49468 and wrapped sashes around each of them, and tied their headbands onto them, just as Yahweh¦49477 had instructed¦49476 Mosheh.
\p
\v 14 Then¦49482 he brought¦49482 the bull for the sin offering, and Aharon¦49487 and his sons placed their¦49491 hands¦49491 on \add *its\add* head.
\v 15 Then \add ?@Aharon\add*\f + \fr 8:15 \ft It's not 100% clear from the Hebrew if the pronoun here refers to Aharon or to Mosheh, but as Mosheh's name is specifically mentioned in the next clause, we assume that ‘he’ was still referring to Aharon here.\f* slaughtered it, and Mosheh took the blood and used his finger¦49510 to put some on the \add four\add* \add ≈projecting corners\add* of the altar, thus purifying the altar. Then he poured¦49518 \add the rest of\add* the blood out at the altar's base, sanctifying it \add ≈so it could be used for making people right with God\add*.
\v 16 Then¦49548 \add @Mosheh\add* took¦49527 all the far that¦49533 was on the innards and the lobe of the liver¦49539, and the two¦49542 kidneys¦49543 and their¦49546 fat, and \add *he\add* burnt them up on the altar¦49549.
\v 17 \add ≈However¦49572,\add* he burnt¦49563 up \add the rest of\add* the bull¦49553 \add ≈including¦49554\add* its hide¦49556, flesh¦49559, and¦49551 dung, outside¦49565 the camp¦49566, just as Yahweh¦49569 had told¦49568 \add *him\add*.
\p
\v 18 Then¦49574 \add @Mosheh\add* presented¦49574 the ram for the burnt¦49577 offering¦49577, and Aharon¦49579 and his sons¦49580 placed their¦49583 hands¦49583 on its head¦49586.
\v 19 Then¦49589 \add ?@Aharon\add*\f + \fr 8:19 \ft It's not 100% clear from the Hebrew if the pronoun here refers to Aharon or to Mosheh, but as Mosheh's name is specifically mentioned in the next clause, we assume that ‘he’ was still referring to Aharon here.\f* slaughtered it, and¦49590 Mosheh splashed the blood¦49594 on \add ≈each side of\add* the altar¦49597.
\v 20 Then¦49600 \add ?@Aharon\add*\f + \fr 8:20 \ft Again it's not 100% clear from the Hebrew if the pronoun here refers to Aharon or to Mosheh, but as Mosheh's name is specifically mentioned in the next clause, we assume that ‘he’ was referring to Aharon (and possibly including his sons) here.\f* cut the ram into pieces, and Mosheh burnt up the head¦49609, and the pieces and the fat.
\v 21 \add ≈However,\add* \add ?@Aharon\add*\f + \fr 8:20 \ft Again it's not 100% clear from the Hebrew if the pronoun here refers to Aharon or to Mosheh, but as Mosheh's name is specifically mentioned in the next clause, we assume that ‘he’ was referring to Aharon here.\f* washed¦49623 the innards and¦49617 the legs, then¦49617 Mosheh \add also\add* burnt \add *those\add* up on the altar¦49632 as a burnt offering that was pleasing¦49637 aroma¦49635 for Yahweh, just as Yahweh had \add ≈instructed¦49642\add* Mosheh.
\p
\v 22 Then¦49648 \add ?@Mosheh\add* presented¦49648 the second¦49652 ram for the ordination offering¦49654, and Aharon¦49656 and his sons¦49657 placed their¦49660 hands¦49660 on the ram's head¦49663.
\v 23 Then¦49666 \add ?@Aharon\add*\f + \fr 8:19 \ft It's not 100% clear from the Hebrew if the pronoun here refers to Aharon or to Mosheh, but as Mosheh's name is specifically mentioned in the next clause, we assume that ‘he’ was still referring to Aharon here.\f* slaughtered it, and Mosheh took¦49668 some of its blood¦49670 and put it on the lobe of Aharon's right ear¦49675, on his right thumb¦49681, and on his right big¦49686 toe¦49686.
\v 24 Then he presented¦49690 Aharon's sons and put some of the blood on their right earlobes, and their right thumbs¦49707, and their right big toes. Then Mosheh splashed the blood on \add ≈each side of\add* the altar¦49722.
\v 25 He \add ≈collected\add* the fat and the fatty tail, and all the fat that¦49737 was on the innards and the lobe of the liver¦49743, and the two¦49746 kidneys¦49747 with their¦49750 fat, and the right¦49753 thigh¦49752,
\v 26 Then¦49755 from the basket¦49755 of unleavened bread that was there \add ≈in front¦49759\add* of Yahweh¦49760, he took one flat bread bun, and one flat bread that had been smeared with oil, and one flat biscuit, and placed them on \add top of\add* the fat and the right¦49777 thigh¦49776.
\v 27 He place \add ≈all that\add* onto the \add ≈open hands\add* of Aharon and¦49779 his sons¦49788 who raised them as a wave offering \add ≈in front¦49792\add* of Yahweh¦49793.
\v 28 Then¦49795 Mosheh¦49796 took \add ≈it all again\add*, and¦49795 burnt it all up on the altar¦49801 with the burnt offering. That ordination offering on the fire¦49809 became a pleasing¦49808 aroma¦49807 for Yahweh¦49811.
\v 29 Then¦49813 Mosheh took the breast¦49817 \add meat\add* from the ram for the ordination offering, and¦49813 raised it as a wave offering \add ≈in front¦49820\add* of Yahweh, just as Yahweh had \add ≈instructed¦49828\add* \add *him\add*.
\p
\v 30 Then¦49834 Mosheh¦49835 took some of the anointing¦49837 oil¦49836 and some of the blood¦49840 from on the altar¦49844, and he \add ≈flicked\add* them onto Aharon and his clothes, his sons and \add *their\add* clothes, thus consecrating¦49860 Aharon and his clothes, and his sons and \add *their\add* clothes.
\p
\v 31 Then¦49876 Mosheh¦49877 told¦49901 Aharon and his sons, “Boil the meat at the entrance¦49888 to the \add ≈sacred¦49889\add* tent and eat it, along with the \add flat\add* bread¦49896 that's in the basket¦49898 \add ≈as part of\add* the ordination offering¦49899, just as I \add ≈had instructed¦49901 that\add* Aharon and his sons should eat it.
\v 32 \add ≈Any\add* meat or bread¦49909 \add ≈that's leftover\add* must¦49911 be burnt in the fire¦49910.
\v 33 None of you may leave the entrance¦49913 to the \add ≈sacred¦49914\add* tent for seven days. \add That's because\add* \add @Yahweh\add* will ordain you all over those seven days.
\v 34 What's been done today has been \add ≈initiated\add* by Yahweh¦49938 in order to make \add ≈you all right with him\add*,
\v 35 \add ≈so\add* remain¦49946 here day¦49947 and night¦49948 at the entrance¦49943 of the \add ≈sacred¦49944\add* tent¦49944 for seven¦49949 days¦49950 as per Yahweh's¦49955 \add ≈instructions¦49961\add* and you all won't¦49956 die¦49957, because that's what I've¦49961 been commanded¦49961.”
\v 36 \add ≈So¦49963\add* Aharon¦49964 and¦49963 his sons¦49965 did everything that¦49970 Yahweh¦49973 had instructed¦49972 them via Mosheh¦49976.
\c 9
\s1 The priests start their duties
\rem /s1 Aaron Offers Sacrifices; Aaron's Priesthood Inaugurated; The Priests Begin Their Work; The Priests Begin Their Ministry
\p
\v 1 On the eighth¦49981 day¦49980, Mosheh¦49983 summoned¦49982 Aharon and his sons¦49985, along with Yisrael's elders¦49986,
\v 2 and he told Aharon, “Get a healthy, \add ≈young¦49997\add*, male calf for a sin offering for yourself¦49995, and a ram \add ≈without¦50003 defects¦50003\add* for a burnt¦50002 offering, and present¦50004 them to Yahweh¦50006.
\v 3 Then¦50008 tell the \add ≈Israeli¦50010 people¦50010\add* to take a male goat¦50015 for a sin offering, and a calf and a lamb¦50020, both a year old and \add ≈without¦50024 defects¦50024\add* for a burnt¦50025 offering,
\v 4 as well as a bull¦50027 and a ram to sacrifice¦50030 to Yahweh as peace¦50029 offerings¦50029, and a grain¦50033 offering¦50033 mixed¦50034 will oil¦50035, because Yahweh will appear¦50039 to you all today.”
\p
\v 5 \add ≈So¦50042\add* they brought \add everything\add* to the \add ≈sacred¦50050\add* tent¦50050 that¦50044 Mosheh¦50046 had \add ≈instructed¦50045\add* them, and¦50042 the whole assembly presented them as they stood¦50056 \add ≈before\add* Yahweh¦50058,
\v 6 then¦50060 Mosheh¦50061 said¦50060, “You've¦50072 done what Yahweh¦50067 told¦50066 you, so now you'll all see his \add ≈brightness\add* appear¦50069.”
\v 7 Then \add *he\add* told¦50102 Aharon, “\add ≈Go\add* to the altar¦50082 and make your sin offering and your burnt¦50089 offering to make \add ≈yourself¦50091 and the people right with God\add*. Then make the people's offering to make \add ≈them right with God\add*, just as Yahweh¦50103 commanded¦50102.”\x + \xo 9:7: \xt Heb 7:27.\x*
\p
\v 8 \add ≈So¦50105\add* Aharon¦50106 approached the altar¦50109 and¦50110 slaughtered the calf for his own sin¦50114 offering¦50114,
\v 9 and¦50119 \add *his\add* sons presented¦50119 the blood to him. Dipping¦50121 his finger¦50127 into the blood, he \add ≈smeared\add* it on the altar's \add four\add* \add ≈projecting corners\add*, then¦50119 he poured¦50137 \add the rest of\add* the blood out at the altar's base.
\v 10 He burnt up the fat and the kidneys¦50148, and the lobe from the liver¦50154 for the sin¦50157 offering¦50157 on the altar¦50159, just as Yahweh¦50162 had instructed¦50161 Mosheh¦50165,
\v 11 \add ≈but¦50167\add* the meat¦50169 and¦50167 the skin¦50172, he burnt¦50173 up in a fire¦50174 outside¦50175 the camp¦50176.
\p
\v 12 Then¦50184 \add ?@Aharon\add* slaughtered the burnt¦50181 offering¦50181, and \add *his\add* sons¦50183 brought¦50182 the blood¦50188 to him and he splashed it on \add ≈each side of\add* the altar¦50192.
\v 13 Then¦50195 they brought¦50198 him the head¦50203 and the \add cut-up\add* pieces¦50200, and he burnt¦50197 them up on the altar¦50207.
\v 14 He washed¦50209 the innards and the legs, and then¦50209 \add also\add* burnt¦50219 them up on the altar¦50220.
\p
\v 15 Then¦50222 \add @Aharon\add* presented¦50222 the people's offering. He took the goat¦50229 for the people's offering and¦50222 slaughtered it, then¦50222 offered it as a sin offering like \add ≈the other one\add*.
\v 16 He presented¦50237 the burnt¦50240 offering¦50240—following all the \add ≈instructions\add* when he did it.
\v 17 Then¦50244 he presented¦50244 the grain¦50247 offering, and¦50244 \add ≈taking a large handful\add*, he burnt it on the altar¦50254, in addition to the morning's¦50257 burnt offering.
\v 18 Then¦50259 \add Aharon¦50272\add* slaughtered the bull¦50262 and the ram \add which¦50268\add* were the people's¦50269 peace¦50267 offering¦50267, and \add *his\add* sons¦50271 brought¦50270 the blood¦50275 to him and he splashed it on \add ≈each side of\add* the altar¦50280.\x + \xo 9:18: \xt Lev 3:1-11.\x*
\v 19 He took the fat from the bull¦50288 and the ram, including¦50289 their fatty tails and \add @the fat\add* covering¦50293 the innards, the kidneys¦50294, and the lobe of the liver¦50296,
\v 20 and¦50305 placed¦50298 it \add all\add* on top of \add &those animals\add* breast¦50304 \add meat\add*, then¦50298 burnt up \add @the fat\add* on the altar¦50307.
\v 21 \add ≈Finally¦50315,\add* he raised the breast¦50310 \add meat\add* and¦50309 the right¦50313 thigh¦50312 as a wave offering \add in front¦50317\add* of Yahweh¦50318, just as Mosheh¦50321 had \add ≈instructed¦50320\add*.
\p
\v 22 Then¦50323 Aharon¦50324 raised his \add ≈arms\add* towards the people¦50331 and blessed¦50332 them, and then¦50323 he \add ≈stepped\add* down, \add having finished\add* making the sin offering, the burnt¦50336 offering, and the peace¦50337 offerings¦50337.\x + \xo 9:22: \xt Num 6:22-26.\x*
\v 23 Mosheh¦50340 and Aharon entered the \add ≈sacred¦50344\add* tent, and \add when\add* they came \add back\add* out, they blessed¦50347 the people and Yahweh's \add ≈brilliance\add* appeared¦50351 to all the people.
\v 24 Then¦50361 flames¦50362 \add ≈shot out\add* from Yahweh's front and \add ≈evaporated\add* the burnt¦50371 offering¦50371 and the fat on the altar¦50368. They people¦50378 saw¦50375 that \add happen\add*, and they yelled out and fell down \add onto their knees\add* \add ≈with their faces¦50383 to the ground\add*.
\c 10
\s1 Nadav and Avihu get destroyed
\rem /s1 The Death of Nadab and Abihu; Nadab and Abihu; The Sin of Nadab and Abihu
\p
\v 1 Then¦50385 two of Aharon's sons, Nadav and Avihu each took their \add ≈incense-burning pans\add* and put fire in them, and put incense on \add @the fire\add*, \add ≈thus offering unauthorised\add* fire to Yahweh¦50401 that¦50404 he hadn't instructed¦50406 them to do.
\v 2 \add ≈So¦50409\add* flames¦50410 \add ≈shot out\add* from Yahweh's front and¦50409 consumed then¦50409 \add ≈so\add* they¦50415 died¦50415 \add there\add* \add ≈in front\add* of Yahweh.
\v 3 Then¦50419 Mosheh¦50420 told Aharon, “That's what Yahweh¦50428 \add ≈meant when he said¦50419\add*, ‘I will \add ≈reveal\add* my holiness to those¦50431 who approach me, then¦50419 I'll¦50432 be honoured \add ≈in the sight of\add* all the people¦50438.’ ”
\p
\v 4 Then¦50443 Mosheh¦50444 \add ≈summoned\add* Mishael¦50447 and Elitsafan, the sons of Aharon's Uncle Uzziyel, and told them, “\add ≈Come and help by carrying¦50457\add* your cousins' \add bodies\add* from the sacred¦50464 place \add here\add* to a place outside¦50467 the camp¦50468.”
\v 5 \add ≈So¦50470\add* they \add ≈came\add* and¦50470 carried¦50471 the two corpses by their¦50472 clothes to a place outside¦50475 the camp¦50476 just as Mosheh¦50479 had told them to do.
\p
\v 6 Then¦50481 Mosheh¦50482 told Aharon and his sons¦50489 Eleazar¦50486 and Itamar¦50487, “Don't \add ≈leave your hair\add* loose, and don't¦50491 tear your clothes¦50495, so that you won't die¦50500 and \add ≡so that\add* \add @Yahweh\add* won't be angry at the entire¦50502 community. But¦50481 \add ≈meanwhile\add*, all the \add ≈Israelis¦50509\add* must¦50500 \add ≈mourn¦50511\add* because Yahweh \add ≈was angry enough to burn\add* \add those two\add*.
\v 7 \add ≈Also,\add* don't¦50522 leave the entrance¦50519 to the \add ≈sacred¦50520\add* tent¦50520, as you might die¦50526 because you all \add still\add* have Yahweh's anointing¦50530 oil¦50529 on you.” \add ≈So¦50519\add* they¦50533 did \add ≈everything that Mosheh¦50535 said\add*.
\s1 Instructions for priests
\rem /s1 Instructions for Priestly Conduct; Rules for Priests
\p
\v 8 Then Yahweh¦50539 told Aharon,
\v 9 “\add Neither\add* you or your sons¦50553 should drink wine or strong¦50546 drink when you're \add going to\add* go into the \add ≈sacred¦50558\add* tent¦50558 so that you won't¦50547 die¦50561. This regulation¦50562 is permanent \add ≈and for future\add* generations¦50564.
\v 10 You must \add carefully\add* \add ≈distinguish\add* between what's sacred¦50568 and what's common, and what's ‘unclean¦50572’ and ‘clean¦50574’.
\v 11 and¦50576 you must teach¦50576 the \add ≈Israelis¦50579\add* all the instructions that¦50585 Yahweh¦50587 has \add ≈given\add* them \add ≈via\add* Mosheh¦50591.”
\p
\v 12 Then Mosheh¦50595 told Aharon and his \add ≈remaining¦50606\add* sons¦50605 Eleazar¦50600 and Itamar¦50603, “Take the remainder of the grain¦50610 offering¦50610 after \add the memorial portion has been given\add* to Yahweh¦50613, and eat¦50614 that¦50611 \add ≈flat bread¦50615\add* \add there\add* beside¦50616 the altar¦50617, because it's \add ≈very sacred¦50619\add*.\x + \xo 10:12-13: \xt Lev 6:14-18.\x*
\v 13 You all must¦50623 eat¦50623 it in a sacred¦50626 place¦50625, because it's the portion for you and¦50623 your sons¦50631 from the gifts to Yahweh¦50634, because that's what I've¦50638 been instructed¦50638.
\v 14 \add ≈Also\add*, you all must¦50647 eat the breast¦50641 \add meat\add* from the wave offering and the thigh¦50645 from the contribution¦50646 \add offering\add* in a ‘clean’ place¦50648. Your sons and daughters¦50652 \add ≈can join you all for that\add*, because \add @that food\add* has been given¦50660 as the portion for you and your children¦50659 from the peace¦50662 offering sacrifices¦50661 from the \add ≈Israelis¦50663\add*.\x + \xo 10:14-15: \xt Lev 7:30-34.\x*
\v 15 \add Yes,\add* \add &those\add* \add #thighs\add* from the contribution¦50667 \add offering\add* and the breast¦50668 \add meat\add* from the wave offering, in addition to the gifts of the fat portions, must¦50673 be brought before Yahweh as a raised offering, and then they'll always become the portion for you and your families, just as Yahweh instructed¦50686.”
\p
\v 16 Then¦50689 Mosheh¦50695 looked for the goat¦50691 \add meat\add* from the sin¦50692 offering¦50692, \add ≈but¦50689 was shocked to discover\add* that it had been burnt¦50697 up \add on the altar\add*, \add ≈so\add* he was angry¦50698 with Aharon's¦50706 remaining¦50707 sons¦50705 Eleazar¦50701 and¦50689 Itamar¦50704, telling them,
\v 17 “Why didn't¦50711 you eat¦50713 \add &that\add* sin¦50716 offering¦50716 in the sacred place¦50717, because it's \add ≈very\add* sacred and he gave¦50725 it to you to bear the community's \add ≈guilt\add* then to \add ≈make them right with\add* Yahweh¦50735.\x + \xo 10:17: \xt Lev 6:24-26.\x*
\v 18 Listen here! Its blood¦50743 \em wasn't\em* taken into the inner sacred place, \add so\add* you must¦50749 eat it in the sacred place just like I told¦50753 you to do!”
\p
\v 19 Then¦50755 Aharon \add ≈explained\add* to Mosheh¦50759, “Listen, they presented¦50762 their sin offering and their burnt¦50768 offering to Yahweh today, and \add ≈yet I lost two of my sons\add*. But¦50755 if I'd eaten the sin offering today, would it have \add ≈pleased\add* Yahweh?”
\v 20 \add ≈When¦50781\add* Mosheh¦50782 heard \add <that\add*, \add ≈he was satisfied\add*.
\c 11
\s1 Creatures that may be eaten
\rem /s1 Animals That May Be Eaten; Ceremonially Clean and Unclean Animals; Clean and Unclean Foods; Clean and Unclean Food; Purification and atonement
\r (Deu. 14:3-21)
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh¦50788 told Mosheh¦50791 and Aharon:
\p
\v 2 Tell¦50802 the \add ≈Israelis¦50801\add* that \add ≈the following\add* creatures¦50805 on the earth¦50814 are the ones that you all can eat¦50807:
\v 3 ⇔You all can eat¦50827 any animal¦50825 that has hooves¦50822 \add ≈which are completely split in two¦50818\add* and¦50820 that \add also\add* \add ≈chew\add* the cud.
\v 4 However you mustn't eat¦50834 those \add ≈without \+em both¦50837\+em* traits\add*, for example camels¦50841 \add ≈chew\add* the cud \add ≈but¦50837\add* don't¦50833 have divided¦50837 hooves¦50838, \add so\add* they are ‘unclean¦50850’ for you.
\v 5 The rock¦50856 badger¦50856 \add ≈likewise\add*, because although it \add ≈chews\add* the cud, it \add too\add* doesn't have divided¦50864 hooves¦50862,
\v 6 and¦50869 the rabbit is ‘unclean¦50880’ for you all because although it \add ≈chews\add* the cud, it doesn't have divided¦50879 hooves¦50877.
\v 7 \add #Pigs\add* have divided¦50889 \add #hooves\add* that are split completely, \add ≈but¦50884\add* don't¦50897 \add ≈chew\add* the cud, \add so\add* they're ‘unclean¦50900’ for you all—
\v 8 you mustn't eat their meat or touch¦50909 their carcasses¦50907 \add because\add* they're ‘unclean¦50910’ for you all.
\p
\v 9 ⇔You all can eat everything that \add lives\add* in the water, \add whether\add* the oceans or rivers, as long as it has \add both\add* fins and scales¦50926.
\v 10 \add ≈In contrast,\add* anything in the oceans or rivers without \add both\add* fins and¦50933 scales¦50939, whether they're swarming¦50943 creatures¦50946 or otherwise, they'll \add all\add* be detestable¦50950 for you all.
\v 11 \add ≈So¦50954\add* anything that's detestable to you all, you mustn't eat their meat and¦50954 you must¦50955 detest¦50954 their carcasses¦50962.
\v 12 Anything in the water¦50972 that doesn't have \add both\add* fins and¦50971 scales¦50971 will be detestable¦50973 for you all.
\p
\v 13 From the birds, the ones that you'll all detest¦50980 and avoid eating will include: the eagle¦50990 and \add ≈any kind of\add* vulture,
\v 14 the kite and¦51000 any kind of falcon,
\v 15 any kind of crow,
\v 16 \add ≈any kind of\add* owl, gull, or hawk,
\v 17 the cormorant¦51030,
\v 18 the osprey,
\v 19 the stork¦51046, any kind of heron¦51047, the hoopoe¦51051, and¦51045 bats.
\v 20 Everything¦51056 that¦51059 swarms¦51057 with wings and walks¦51059 on four¦51062 \add legs\add* must be detestable¦51063 for you all.
\v 21 However, you all can eat¦51072 anything that swarms¦51074 with wings and walks¦51076 on four¦51079 \add legs\add* that has its legs above¦51085 its feet¦51086 for hopping on the ground.
\v 22 You all can eat any kind of locust or cricket or grasshopper¦51112,
\v 23 \add ≈but¦51115\add* anything that¦51118 swarms¦51116 with wings and¦51115 walks on four¦51121 \add legs\add* must be detestable¦51123 for you all.
\rem /s1 Unclean Animals
\p
\v 24 \add ≈The following\add* will make you¦51128 ‘unclean’—anyone¦51131 who touches¦51131 their¦51132 carcasses¦51132 will become ‘unclean’ until¦51134 the evening¦51136,
\v 25 plus¦51144 anyone¦51140 who carries¦51140 their carcass¦51141 must¦51142 wash their clothes¦51143 and¦51138 will be ‘unclean¦51144’ until¦51145 the evening¦51147:
\v 26 Any animal with a divided¦51154 hoof¦51155 but¦51156 not \add ≈completely split in two¦51154\add* or that¦51152 doesn't \add ≈chew\add* the cud will be ‘unclean’ for you all—anyone¦51168 who touches¦51168 them will become ‘unclean’.
\v 27 \add ≈Also,\add* any four-footed animal that¦51174 walks on its paws is ‘unclean’ for you—anyone¦51174 who touches¦51190 their¦51191 carcass¦51191 will become ‘unclean’ until¦51193 the evening¦51195,
\v 28 plus¦51203 anyone¦51197 who carries¦51197 their carcass¦51200 must¦51201 wash their clothes¦51202 and¦51197 will be ‘unclean’ until¦51204 the evening¦51206 \add because\add* they're ‘unclean’ for you all.
\p
\v 29 These are the ‘unclean¦51214’ creatures from the ones that¦51216 swarm¦51216 on the ground: \add #rats, mice, lizards¦51222\add*
\v 30 of any kind, \add #geckos, skinks¦51228, and¦51225 chameleons¦51229\add*.
\v 31 Out of all the swarming¦51236 things¦51236, those are ‘unclean’ for you—anyone¦51239 who touches¦51239 them when they've died will be ‘unclean’ until¦51243 the evening¦51245.
\v 32 \add ≈Also,\add* anything that¦51272 \add ≈their¦51255 dead bodies\add* fall on will become ‘unclean’, whether it's a wooden. cloth, leader, or sackcloth¦51268 object, or any container used for work¦51275, \add so then¦51247\add* it must¦51250 be immersed in water¦51277 and¦51247 it will be ‘unclean’ until¦51280 the evening¦51282 when it will become ‘clean’ \add again\add*.
\v 33 \add If\add* one of \add @those creatures\add* falls into a clay container, everything in it will become ‘unclean¦51300’ and¦51285 you must¦51292 break¦51302 \add @that container\add*.
\v 34 If water¦51312 from \add that container\add* got onto any food, it will become ‘unclean’, and any drink¦51316 \add ≈take\add* from that container will be ‘unclean’.
\v 35 Anything that the dead body of one of \add @those creatures\add* falls onto will become ‘unclean’—any oven or stove¦51333 must¦51327 be smashed. They have become ‘unclean’ \add ≈and¦51324 would always remain so\add*.
\v 36 However a spring¦51342 or a cistern¦51343 for collecting¦51344 water¦51346 will be ‘clean’, \add ≈but¦51343\add* anyone¦51349 touching¦51349 that dead body will be ‘unclean¦51351’.
\v 37 If the dead body fell on some seeds that will be planted, \add @that seed\add* is still ‘clean’,
\v 38 \add ≈but¦51367\add* if the seeds \add ≈are wet\add* when the dead body falls on it, then¦51367 it's ‘unclean¦51377’ for you.
\p
\v 39 If any animal that¦51387 you all can eat dies, then any person touches¦51392 its¦51393 carcass¦51393 will be ‘unclean¦51394’ until¦51395 the evening¦51397.
\v 40 Anyone¦51399 who eats¦51399 any \add part\add* of that dead body, and anyone¦51399 who \add ≈moves\add* it, must¦51401 wash their clothes¦51402 and will be ‘unclean’ until the evening.
\p
\v 41 Every creature that¦51421 swarms¦51420 along the ground is detestable¦51425—it mustn't be eaten¦51428.
\v 42 Everything that \add moves\add* on its belly, and any swarming thing that moves along the ground on four¦51441 or more feet mustn't be eaten because they're detestable.
\v 43 Don't make yourselves detestable¦51463 with any of those swarming¦51469 creatures, and don't¦51461 make yourselves ‘unclean’ by \add touching or eating\add* them,
\v 44 because I am your god¦51480 Yahweh¦51479. You all must¦51481 keep¦51481 yourselves holy, and you're a holy people because I'm holy. \add ≈So\add* don't¦51487 make yourselves ‘unclean¦51488’ with any swarming¦51494 creatures that creep¦51495 across the ground\x + \xo 11:44: \xt Lev 19:2; 1Pe 1:16.\x*
\v 45 because I am Yahweh¦51503, the one who brought¦51504 you all out of Egypt¦51507 to be your god¦51510, and you must¦51511 be holy because I am holy.
\p
\v 46 The \add above\add* are the regulations about livestock, birds, creatures that move in the water¦51525, and creatures that swarm¦51529 across the ground,
\v 47 to \add ≈distinguish\add* between the ‘unclean¦51536’ and the ‘clean’, i.e., those that can be eaten and those that must¦51546 not be eaten.
\c 12
\s1 Purification after giving birth
\rem /s1 The Purification of Women after Childbirth; Purification after Childbirth; Purification of Women after Childbirth; Purification After Childbirth
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh¦51550 told Mosheh¦51553:
\p
\v 2 Tell¦51560 the \add ≈Israelis¦51559\add* that when a woman¦51562 gets pregnant and then gives birth to a boy, she will then be ‘unclean’ for seven¦51568 days similar to how her impurity¦51571 during her \add ≈monthly period\add* makes her ‘unclean’.
\v 3 Then¦51575 on the eighth¦51576 day¦51575, \add @the baby boy's\add* foreskin¦51579 must¦51577 be circumcised¦51577.\x + \xo 12:3: \xt Gen 17:12; Luk 2:21.\x*
\v 4 \add @The mother\add* will remain¦51585 impure from the blood¦51586 for thirty-three days—she must¦51585 not touch¦51593 any sacred¦51590 thing¦51590 and¦51581 may not enter the sanctuary¦51596 until¦51599 her¦51602 purification time¦51584 is completed¦51601.
\p
\v 5 \add ≈However,\add* if she gave birth to a \add ≈girl\add*, she'll be ‘unclean¦51609’ for two¦51610 weeks¦51610 similar to how her impurity¦51611 during her \add ≈monthly period\add*, and¦51605 her purification¦51620 time¦51615 will be sixty-six days¦51615.
\p
\v 6 When¦51622 \add @the mother's\add* purification¦51625 time¦51624 is completed¦51622 for either a son or a daughter¦51628, she must¦51629 take a one-year-old lamb as a burnt¦51634 offering and¦51622 a \add ≈young¦51635\add* pigeon or dove as a sin offering to the priest¦51650 at the entrance¦51644 to the \add ≈sacred¦51645\add* tent.
\v 7 Then¦51652 he must¦51652 present¦51652 them to Yahweh¦51654 to \add ≈make her right with God\add*, and¦51652 then¦51652 she'll be purified from her flow of blood¦51659. That's the regulation for a woman who gives¦51662 birth¦51662 to either a male or a female¦51665.
\p
\v 8 If \add ≈she's unable to afford\add* a lamb, then she must¦51670 take \em two\em* young¦51680 pigeons or doves—one for the burnt¦51683 offering and one for the sin offering. Then¦51667 the priest¦51688 will \add ≈make her¦51671 right with God\add*, and then she'll will have been purified.\x + \xo 12:8: \xt Luk 2:24.\x*
\c 13
\s1 Regulations about skin diseases
\rem /s1 Laws concerning Skin Diseases; Contagious Skin Diseases; Leprosy, Varieties and Symptoms; Regulations About Infectious Skin Diseases
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh¦51693 told Mosheh¦51696 and Aharon:
\p
\v 2 If \add someone discovers\add* a raised area on their skin, or a scab or a bright¦51714 spot, and it seems like an infectious skin disease¦51720, then \add @that person\add* should be taken to a priest¦51725 (Aharon or one of his sons¦51730),
\v 3 and the priest must \add ≈examine\add* their skin. If the hair¦51741 in the infected \add spot\add* has turned¦51743 white¦51745 and the infection appears¦51746 to be deeper under the skin, then¦51733 it's \add confirmed as\add* an infectious skin disease¦51752 and \add ≈so\add* the priest must pronounce the person as ‘unclean¦51756’.
\v 4 \add However,\add* if it's a white spot \add ≈that doesn't seem\add* to be deep, and¦51759 the hair¦51773 hasn't turned¦51776 white, then¦51759 the priest¦51779 \add must¦51778 order\add* the person to be quarantined for seven¦51783 days¦51784.
\v 5 Then¦51786 on the seventh day¦51788, if the infection is still there but¦51786 hasn't spread¦51796, then¦51786 the priest \add must¦51786 order\add* a further seven¦51801 days¦51802 of quarantine.
\v 6 After that next seven¦51809 days, if the infection has faded and not spread¦51816, the priest must pronounce the person as ‘clean’—it was just a \add ≈sore\add* so the person must wash their clothes¦51824 and then¦51805 they'll be ‘clean’.
\v 7 \add ≈However,\add* if the spot does spread across the skin \em after¦51833\em* the priest has pronounced \add @the person\add* to be ‘clean’, then¦51827 they must¦51830 \add ≈return\add* to the priest a second¦51840 time.
\v 8 The priest must re-examine \add @that person\add* and¦51845 if the spot on the skin has spread¦51848, then¦51845 the priest must pronounce them ‘unclean¦51851’ because they have a skin disease¦51853.
\p
\v 9 Anyone who develops an infectious skin disease¦51858 must¦51860 be taken to a priest¦51865
\v 10 \add ≈to be examined\add*. If it's a white spot on the skin and the hair¦51876 has turned¦51875 white, and there's raw flesh¦51879 \add visible\add* in the swelling,
\v 11 then it's a chronic skin disease¦51883, and the priest¦51889 must¦51888 pronounce \add @that person\add* as ‘unclean’ and can't¦51890 just be \add temporarily\add* \add ≈quarantined\add*.
\v 12 \add ≈However,\add* if the disease has broken out and¦51896 spread across the entire¦51905 \add ≈body\add* from head¦51909 to toe as far as can be observed by the priest¦51917,
\v 13 then¦51919 \add after\add* the priest's¦51920 confirmation that it covers¦51922 the entire¦51926 \add ≈body¦51928\add*, \add @that person\add* can be pronounced as ‘clean’ \add again\add* as all of it has turned¦51934 white¦51935.
\v 14 \add ≈However,\add* if any raw flesh¦51942 \add ≈shows itself\add*, then¦51939 they'll become ‘unclean¦51944’ \add ≈that same\add* day¦51939.
\v 15 The priest¦51947 must \add ≈examine\add* that raw flesh and¦51952 must pronounce \add @that person\add* as ‘unclean’ due to \add &their\add* skin disease¦51957.
\v 16 \add ≈Afterwards, if it heals over\add* and goes white¦51966, then they can return¦51962 to the priest¦51970
\v 17 \add ≈to be reexamined\add*, and if the infection has indeed gone white¦51977, then¦51972 the priest can pronounce it as \add ≈not being infectious\add* and \add @the person\add* as ‘clean’ \add again\add*.
\p
\v 18 When \add ≈someone\add* has a boil on their skin, \add ≈but¦51987\add* it heals
\v 19 \add ≈leaving behind\add* a white swelling¦52000 or a reddish-white bright¦52003 spot, then¦51997 \add @that person\add* must¦52006 show themself to the priest¦52009.
\v 20 The priest will \add ≈examine\add* it, and if it is indeed more than \add just\add* skin deep and its hair¦52019 has turned¦52020 white¦52021, then¦52011 the priest must¦52011 pronounce \add @that person\add* as ‘unclean¦52022’ because an infectious skin disease¦52026 has broken¦52029 out from the \add original\add* boil.
\v 21 \add ≈However,\add* if the priest's examination finds not white¦52040 hair¦52039 on it, and it's not more than skin deep, and it's fading, then¦52031 he will \add order\add* \add @that person\add* quarantined for seven¦52050 days¦52051,
\v 22 and¦52053 if it spreads further on \add &their\add* skin, then¦52053 the priest¦52059 must¦52056 declare¦52058 \add @that person\add* as ‘unclean¦52058’ because it's \add ≈infectious\add*.
\v 23 \add ≈But¦52064\add* if the bright¦52068 spot \add ≈hasn't spread¦52070\add* \add during the quarantine\add*, then¦52064 it's \add just\add* the scar from the boil and¦52074 the priest¦52075 can pronounce \add @the person\add* as ‘clean’.
\p
\v 24 If someone gets a burn on their skin, and the burn area becomes reddish-white or a white spot,
\v 25 then the priest must examine it, and if the hair¦52101 on the spot has turned¦52100 white¦52102 and \add @the infection\add* looks more than skin deep, then a skin disease has broken¦52112 out in the burn¦52111, and the priest must pronounce \add @that person\add* as ‘unclean¦52113’ because it's \add ≈infectious\add*.
\v 26 \add ≈However,\add* if the priest sees that there's¦52125 no white¦52129 hair¦52128 in the spot, and it's not more than skin deep, and it's fading, then¦52120 \add *he\add* will \add order\add* \add @that person\add* quarantined for seven¦52139 days¦52140.
\v 27 On the seventh¦52145 day¦52144, the priest will re-examine \add @the person\add*, and¦52151 if it's spread further, \add *he\add* must¦52142 pronounce \add @that person\add* as ‘unclean¦52151’ because it's an infectious skin disease¦52155.
\v 28 \add ≈But¦52158\add* if the bright¦52162 spot hasn't spread¦52165 on the skin, and¦52158 it faded \add more\add*, then¦52158 it was \add just\add* swelling¦52169 from the burn. Then¦52158 the priest¦52173 will pronounce \add @that person\add* to be ‘clean’ because it was \add just\add* the scar \add ≈caused by\add* \add &their\add* burn.
\p
\v 29 If a man or woman¦52183 has an infection in \add &their\add* \add ≈scalp\add* or \add ≈under\add* \add &their\add* beard¦52191,
\v 30 then the priest should inspect the infection. If it appears¦52199 to be more than skin deep, and there's any thin yellow¦52206 hairs in it, then the priest must¦52193 pronounce \add @that person\add* as ‘unclean¦52208’ \add because\add* it's a \add ≈itchy and infectious\add* skin infection on the \add ≈scalp or face\add*.
\v 31 \add ≈However,\add* if the priest notices an itchy infection yet it's only skin deep and¦52219 there's¦52237 no black¦52236 hair¦52235 on it, then¦52219 he should quarantine that person for seven¦52245 days¦52246.
\v 32 On the seventh¦52254 day¦52253, the priest¦52249 will re-examine \add ≈that person\add* and if the spot hasn't widened and \add still\add* only appears¦52266 to be skin deep,
\v 33 then \add @that person\add* should shave \add their head\add*, and¦52274 then the priest¦52281 should quarantine them for a further seven¦52285 days¦52286.
\v 34 Then¦52289 \add again\add* on the seventh¦52295 day¦52294, the priest will inspect it, and if the spot hasn't widened after being shaved and it doesn't seem to be more than skin deep, then¦52289 the priest can pronounce \add @that person\add* as ‘clean’ \add ≈once\add* they've washed their clothes¦52312.
\v 35 \add ≈However,\add* it¦52318 is did spread on their skin after¦52321 \add *that\add*,
\v 36 then the priest must¦52324 inspect it again, and¦52324 if it's spread¦52327 then \add @that person\add* is ‘unclean¦52336’ (whether or not there's any yellow¦52335 hair¦52334).
\v 37 \add ≈But¦52339\add* if it seems that the spot \add ≈hasn't spread\add* and dark hair¦52344 is growing in it again, then¦52339 \add @that person's\add* \add ≈not infectious\add* and the priest¦52354 can pronounce them as ‘clean’.
\p
\v 38 If a man or woman¦52360 \add ≈finds very\add* white¦52369 spots on their¦52366 skin,
\v 39 then the priest¦52372 must¦52371 examine \add <them\add*. If the spots¦52377 on their¦52376 skin are dull white¦52379, then it's a skin rash that's broken¦52382 out and¦52373 they are ‘clean’.
\p
\v 40 If a man's head¦52391 has become¦52390 bare, then he's \add gone\add* bald and¦52388 is \add still\add* ‘clean’.
\v 41 \add ≈Similarly, \add* if the hair \add ≈is receding\add* from the front corners, he's \add ≈going bald\add* and¦52397 is \add still\add* ‘clean’.
\v 42 \add ≈However,\add* if there's a balding spot with a reddish-white infection, it's a skin disease¦52416 breaking¦52417 out via that¦52417 spot
\v 43 and¦52426 the priest¦52425 must¦52423 examine him. If it's a balding spot with a reddish-white infection that looks like a \add contagious\add* skin disease¦52436,
\v 44 then he's \add ≈contagious\add* and ‘unclean’. The priest¦52448 must¦52447 pronounce his as ‘unclean’ because of that infection on his head¦52449.
\p
\v 45 Anyone¦52452 who's developed an infectious skin disease¦52452 must tear their clothes¦52457 and \add ≈leave their hair loose\add*, and must \add ≈cover¦52466 their mouth\add* and call out, ‘Unclean, unclean.’
\v 46 They will remain ‘unclean’ as long as they \add still\add* have that¦52475 infection, and must¦52478 live alone¦52481 outside¦52483 the camp¦52484.
\s1 Regulations about moulds and fungi
\rem /s1 Laws concerning Mildew; Regulations About Mildew; Treatment of Contaminated Clothing
\p
\v 47 When a \add piece of\add* clothing has a mould growing on it, whether it's made of wool or linen¦52499,
\v 48 or whether it's something woven from wool or linen¦52505, or something made from leather,
\v 49 if the growth is greenish¦52517 or reddish¦52520 in colour, then¦52515 it's something that can spread and¦52515 it must¦52539 be shown¦52539 to the priest¦52542.
\v 50 The priest¦52545 must¦52544 examine the growth, and¦52549 quarantine the \add ≈article\add* for seven¦52553 days¦52554.
\v 51 On the seventh¦52561 day¦52560, if the growth has spread on that piece of material or leather equipment, and it's confirmed as spreadable and is ‘unclean¦52584’.
\v 52 \add ?@The owner\add* must burn¦52587 the piece of clothing or equipment that¦52610 contains the infection because it's contagious, so it must be completely burnt¦52621 up.
\p
\v 53 \add ≈However\add* if the priest¦52625 notices that the growth hasn't spread¦52629 on the clothing or on the woven or leather \add ≈material\add*,
\v 54 then the priest¦52644 must¦52643 order that¦52647 the \add ≈material\add* be washed and¦52643 then quarantined for a \add ≈further\add* seven¦52652 days¦52654.
\v 55 \add On the seventh day,\add* the priest¦52658 must inspect that washed¦52661 \add ≈material\add*, and if the growth hasn't \add ≈changed its appearance\add*, even if it hasn't spread¦52676, then¦52657 it's ‘unclean¦52677’ and must be burnt in the fire¦52679—it's a mildew¦52681 that's on the front¦52685 or back of the material.
\v 56 \add ≈However,\add* if the priest¦52689 notices that the growth has faded after¦52693 being washed¦52694, then¦52687 it can be torn out of the clothing¦52700 or piece of leather or woven material.
\v 57 If it \add then\add* reappears on that clothing or material, then it's breaking¦52731 out, so then that article¦52728 must¦52716 be burnt in the fire¦52733.
\v 58 \add ≈On the other hand,\add* if the growth \add ≈vanished after being\add* washed, then it must¦52755 be washed a second¦52760 time and¦52741 then it will be ‘clean’.
\p
\v 59 \add @The above\add* are the regulations concerning any growth on a piece of woollen or linen¦52772 clothing¦52768 or fabric, or any leather article¦52780, to pronounce it ‘clean’ or ‘unclean¦52785’.
\c 14
\s1 Purification after a skin disease
\rem /s1 Purification after Having Skin Diseases; Cleansing from Skin Diseases; Purification of Lepers and Leprous Houses; Cleansing From Infectious Skin Diseases
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh¦52789 told Mosheh¦52792:
\p
\v 2 These are the regulations for the purification¦52800 of a person who had a skin disease¦52798. They must¦52796 be taken to a priest¦52804\x + \xo 14:2: \xt Mat 8:4; Mrk 1:44; Luk 5:14; 17:14.\x*
\v 3 \add *who'll\add* go¦52806 outside¦52810 the camp¦52811 \add to meet them\add*. The priest must¦52806 inspect \add that person\add*, and¦52806 if the skin disease has indeed left them,
\v 4 then¦52823 the priest¦52824 will order them to bring \add <him\add* two¦52827 live, ‘clean’ birds¦52829, some cedar¦52833 \add wood\add*, some scarlet¦52834 \add thread\add*, and¦52823 some hyssop¦52836 \add twigs\add*.
\v 5 The priest¦52839 must¦52838 tell \add @the person\add* to slaughter one bird \add ?≈so the blood runs into\add* a clay jug \add ?≈containing\add* water¦52852 \add ≈from a spring or creek\add*.
\v 6 Then \add @the priest\add* will take¦52859 the live bird, along with the cedar¦52864 wood, the scarlet¦52867 \add thread\add*, and the hyssop¦52871 \add twigs\add*, and dip them \add ≈all\add* into that¦52880 blood¦52878 of the slaughtered bird (\add ?≈mixed with\add* the \add ≈fresh\add* water¦52882),
\v 7 and \add ≈flick\add* it seven¦52891 times¦52892 onto the person who's being purified¦52887 from the skin disease¦52890. Then¦52885 \add @the priest\add* can pronounce them as ‘clean’ \add enough to re-enter the community\add*, and \add ≈release\add* the live bird \add to fly\add* into the countryside¦52902.
\v 8 The person who's being purified¦52905 must then wash their clothes¦52908, shave¦52909 all their hair¦52914, and¦52904 then bathe in \add flowing\add* water¦52916. After that, they can re-enter the camp¦52922 \add ≈but¦52904\add* must live outside¦52924 their tent¦52925 for seven¦52926 \add more\add* days¦52927.
\v 9 On the seventh¦52931 day¦52930, \add @that person\add* must¦52932 shave off all their hair (including¦52941 eyebrows¦52945 and beard¦52943 \add if appropriate\add*), wash their clothes¦52956 and bathe themself in \add flowing\add* water¦52961, then¦52929 they'll be ‘clean’.
\p
\v 10 Then¦52964 on the eighth¦52965 day¦52964, \add @that person\add* must¦52966 \add ≈get\add* two one-year-old \add male\add* lambs¦52969, and¦52964 one female lamb, \add all\add* \add ≈with no defects\add*, along with three¦52977 kilograms of fine flour¦52979 mixed¦52981 with oil as a grain¦52980 offering¦52980, as well as \add ≈half a litre\add* of \add olive\add* oil.
\v 11 \add That must¦52987 be taken to\add* the priest¦52988 who'd pronounced them as ‘clean’ \add ≈will accompany them\add* and¦52993 all those offerings to stand \add ≈in front¦52994\add* of Yahweh¦52995 at the entrance¦52996 to the \add ≈sacred¦52997\add* tent¦52997.
\v 12 Then¦53000 the priest¦53001 must¦53000 take one of the male lambs and the \add ≈container\add* of oil and present¦53006 it as a guilt¦53008 offering, then¦53000 he'll raise them as a wave offering \add ≈in front¦53016\add* of Yahweh¦53017.
\v 13 Then¦53019 \add @that person\add* must¦53019 slaughter that lamb¦53022 in the sacred place where¦53024 sin offerings and¦53019 burnt¦53031 offerings are slaughtered, because this guilt¦53036 offering is like a sin offering in that it's for the priest¦53038—it's \add ≈very\add* sacred.
\v 14 Then¦53043 the priest must¦53043 take¦53043 some of the blood¦53045 from that guilt¦53046 offering¦53046, and put it on the lobe of the right ear¦53052 of the person being purified¦53053, and on their right thumb¦53057 and right big¦53062 toe¦53062.
\v 15 Then¦53066 the priest must¦53066 take¦53066 \add ≈the container\add* of olive oil¦53069 and¦53070 pour some into his left hand.
\v 16 Then¦53077 he'll dip his right¦53082 finger into that oil on his left palm, and¦53077 with that \add same\add* finger, \add ≈flick\add* it seven¦53096 times¦53097 \add ≈towards\add* Yahweh¦53099.
\v 17 Then¦53101 the priest¦53108 must¦53107 put some of the remaining¦53101 oil¦53102 on his palm¦53106 onto the lobe of the right ear¦53112 of the person being purified¦53113, and on their right thumb¦53117 and right big¦53122 toe¦53122—on top of the blood¦53126 from the guilt¦53127 offering¦53127.
\v 18 Then¦53129 the priest will put \add all\add* the remaining¦53129 oil¦53130 from his palm¦53134 onto the head¦53139 of the person being purified¦53140, and¦53141 the priest \add ≈will then¦53129 make that¦53131 person right with\add* Yahweh¦53145.
\p
\v 19 Then¦53147 the priest¦53148 must¦53147 make the sin offering and¦53147 \add ≈make that person right\add* after¦53157 being purified¦53155 from their ‘uncleanness¦53156’. After that \add ?@that person\add* will slaughter \add lamb for\add* the burnt¦53161 offering.
\v 20 Then¦53163 the priest must¦53163 offer \add &that\add* burnt¦53167 offering and the grain¦53170 offering \add ≈on the fire\add* on the altar¦53171 and he will make \add ≈that person right again\add* and he will be ‘clean¦53175’.
\p
\v 21 \add ≈However,\add* if \add @that person\add* is poor and \add ≈cannot afford\add* \add the multiple lambs\add*, then they must¦53185 take \em one\em* lamb¦53186 to wave as the guilt¦53188 offering and to make \add ≈them right again\add*, along with \em one\em* kilogram of fine flour¦53193 mixed¦53195 with oil for the grain¦53197 offering, and the half litre of oil,
\v 22 plus¦53210 two doves or \add ≈young¦53205\add* pigeons—whichever¦53207 they can afford—one for a sin offering and¦53201 the other for the burnt¦53214 offering.
\v 23 Then¦53216 on \add &that\add* eighth¦53219 day¦53218, he'll take them to the priest¦53223 at the entrance¦53226 of the \add ≈sacred¦53227\add* tent¦53227 for purification¦53220 \add ≈in front¦53230\add* of Yahweh¦53231.
\v 24 Then¦53233 the priest should take the guilt¦53238 offering lamb¦53237 and the \add ≈container\add* of oil and lift them up as a wave offering \add ≈in front¦53247\add* of Yahweh¦53248.
\v 25 Then¦53250 \add ?@the person\add* should slaughter \add &that\add* guilt offering lamb¦53253, and the priest¦53256 must¦53250 take some of \add ≈that\add* blood¦53257 and put it on the lobe of the right ear¦53263 of the person being purified¦53265, and on their right thumb¦53269 and right big toe.
\v 26 Then¦53278 \add *he\add* must¦53281 pour some of the oil¦53280 onto \add *his\add* left palm¦53285
\v 27 and¦53289 with his right¦53292 finger¦53291 he must¦53289 \add ≈flick\add* it seven¦53301 times¦53302 \add ≈towards\add* Yahwh¦53304.
\v 28 Then¦53306 the priest¦53307 must put some of the oil¦53310 from his palm¦53315 onto the lobe of the right ear¦53319 of the person being purified¦53320, and on their right thumb¦53324 and right big¦53329 toe¦53329—on top of the blood¦53335 from the guilt¦53336 offering¦53336.
\v 29 Then¦53338 the priest will put \add all\add* the remaining¦53338 oil¦53341 from his palm¦53345 onto the head¦53350 of the person being purified¦53351, and¦53338 the priest \add ≈will then¦53338 make that¦53342 person right with\add* Yahweh¦53355.
\v 30 Then¦53357 he must¦53357 \add ≈offer¦53357\add* one of the birds (dove¦53368 or pigeon—whatever \add @that person\add* \add ≈could afford\add*)
\v 31 as a sin offering and \add ≈the other\add* as a burnt¦53385 offering along with the grain¦53388 offering and he will make \add ≈that¦53374 person right again with\add* Yahweh¦53394.
\v 32 \add The above\add* are the regulations for anyone who has a skin disease¦53402 \add ≈but who couldn't afford the regular purification¦53408 offerings\add*.
\s1 Treating contaminated homes
\rem /s1 Cleansing From Mildew; Mildew in Houses; Treatment of Contaminated Houses
\p
\v 33 Then Yahweh¦53412 told Mosheh¦53415 and Aharon:
\p
\v 34 “\add ≈When\add* you enter into the land of Kanaan which¦53427 I'm giving you all as a possession, and if I \add ≈cause\add* an infection in one your¦53437 homes in \add *that\add* land,
\v 35 then¦53439 the homeowner must¦53439 go and¦53439 inform the priest¦53445 that something like an infection has appeared¦53448 in their house.
\v 36 The priest must¦53452 order that everything be removed out of the house before¦53458 \add *he\add* comes to \add ≈inspect it\add* \add ≈so that\add* it won't¦53465 all be pronounced as ‘unclean¦53466’. After \add ≈that's done\add*, he'll go to see the house
\v 37 and \add ≈examine\add* the growth. If the growth is greenish¦53489 or reddish¦53491 and seems more than surface deep,
\v 38 then¦53498 the priest¦53499 must¦53498 leave the house via the \add main\add* entrance¦53505 and¦53498 quarantine the house for seven¦53511 days¦53512.
\v 39 On the seventh¦53517 day¦53516, the priest¦53515 must¦53514 return¦53514 and \add ≈examine it¦53520\add* \add again\add*, and if the growth has spread¦53520 on the house¦53523 walls¦53522,
\v 40 then¦53525 \add *he\add* must¦53525 order that those infected stones¦53530 be pulled out of the wall and¦53525 thrown¦53534 outside¦53538 the city¦53539 into a place¦53542 \add that's considered\add* ‘unclean¦53543’.
\v 41 Then¦53545 \add the homeowner\add* must¦53548 scrape¦53548 \add ≈all the plaster off the inside¦53549 walls\add* and¦53551 \add also\add* \add ≈dispose of that\add* at \add &that\add* ‘unclean¦53564’ place¦53563.
\v 42 Then¦53566 they \add ≈can replace the stones that were removed\add*, and¦53566 \add ≈apply fresh plaster¦53577\add* to the house¦53580.
\p
\v 43 \add ≈However,\add* if the growth returns¦53584 and breaks¦53586 out \add again\add* in the house \add even\add* after \add ≈the stones¦53592 were replaced and the walls were replastered\add*,
\v 44 then the priest¦53602 must¦53601 come \add back\add* and \add ≈reexamine\add* it. If the growth has spread¦53605 \add ≈on the walls\add*, then it's a malignant¦53609 growth and \add @the house\add* is ‘unclean¦53612’.
\v 45 \add @The owner\add* must tear the house down—its stones¦53621 and timber and all the mortar, must be \add ≈carted\add* outside¦53633 the city¦53634 into a place¦53637 \add that's considered\add* ‘unclean¦53638’.
\v 46 Any person that enters that house¦53643 \add ≈after the priest had quarantined it\add*, will be ‘unclean¦53649’ until¦53650 \add &that\add* evening¦53652.
\v 47 Any person who lies down or eats in that house, must¦53656 wash their clothes¦53659.
\p
\v 48 \add ≈However,\add* if the priest \add ≈came back\add* after the house was replastered and¦53667 \add ≈after his inspection, find that\add* the growth \add ≈hasn't reappeared\add*, then¦53667 \add *he\add* can pronounce the house as ‘clean’ because the \add ≈growth has gone\add*.
\v 49 Then he must¦53694 take¦53694 two¦53699 birds¦53700, cedar¦53702 wood, scarlet¦53703 \add ≈thread\add*, and some hyssop¦53705 \add twigs\add*,
\v 50 and¦53707 slaughter one bird \add ?≈so the blood runs into\add* a clay jug \add ?≈containing\add* water¦53719 \add ≈from a spring or creek\add*.
\v 51 Then¦53722 \add ?@the priest\add* must¦53722 take¦53722 the live bird, along with the cedar¦53727 wood, the scarlet¦53733 \add thread\add*, the hyssop¦53730 \add twigs\add* and the live bird, and dip them \add ≈all\add* into that¦53742 blood¦53740 of the slaughtered bird (\add ?≈mixed with\add* the \add ≈fresh\add* water¦53743), and \add ≈flick\add* it seven¦53749 times¦53750 onto the house¦53748.
\v 52 \add In that way,\add* he'll purify the house¦53755 with the bird's blood¦53756 and the \add ≈fresh\add* water¦53758, and with the live bird and the cedar¦53763 \add wood\add*, the hyssop¦53764 \add twigs\add* and the scarlet¦53765 \add thread\add*.
\v 53 Then¦53768 he must¦53768 \add ≈release\add* the live bird \add to fly\add* into the countryside¦53780, \add ≈thus\add* making the house¦53784 \add ≈right with God\add*, and¦53768 then¦53768 it'll be ‘clean’.
\p
\v 54 \add @The above\add* are the regulations concerning any serious¦53792 skin diseases¦53792 and¦53793 itchiness,
\v 55 as well as growths on clothing¦53796 and¦53797 \add ≈buildings\add*
\v 56 and swellings¦53799, rashes, and bright spots \add on the skin\add*,
\v 57 \add ≈so that you'll know how to determine what's\add* ‘unclean¦53805’ or ‘clean’. Those are the regulations for \add ≈infectious growths\add*.
\c 15
\s1 The laws of sicknesses eglihawang of body of person
\rem /s1 Bodily Discharges; Unclean Bodily Discharges; Discharges Causing Uncleanness; Concerning Bodily Discharges
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh¦53814 told Mosheh¦53817 and Aaron¦53820:
\p
\v 2 Tell the \add ≈Israelis¦53826\add* that whenever any man has a discharge¦53834 from his \add ≈genitals\add*, then he becomes ‘unclean¦53837’.
\v 3 He becomes ‘unclean’ whether his body¦53845 secretes¦53844 the flow or if it's blocked—either way he's ‘unclean’.
\v 4 Any bed that¦53860 he was lying on during \add or after\add* the discharge¦53863 becomes ‘unclean’, as does anything he sits on.
\v 5 Anyone who touches¦53876 that bed must¦53876 wash their clothes¦53879 and bathe themself in water¦53881, and \add @that person\add* will be ‘unclean¦53882’ until¦53883 the evening¦53885.
\v 6 \add ≈Similarly,\add* anyone¦53887 who sits¦53887 on the place where he sat must¦53893 wash their clothes¦53897 and bathe themself in water¦53899, and \add @that person\add* will be ‘unclean¦53900’ until¦53901 the evening¦53903.
\v 7 Anyone¦53905 who touches¦53905 the man who had a discharge¦53907 must¦53908 wash their clothes¦53909 and bathe themself in water¦53911, and \add @that person\add* will be ‘unclean¦53912’ until¦53913 the evening¦53915.
\v 8 If that man who had a discharge¦53920 spits on some person who was ‘clean’, then¦53917 \add @that person\add* must¦53919 wash their clothes¦53923 and bathe themself in water¦53925, and they will be ‘unclean¦53926’ until¦53927 the evening¦53929.
\v 9 Any thing that¦53934 the man who had a discharge¦53937 rides on, will become ‘unclean¦53938’,
\v 10 and anyone who touches¦53942 it¦53945 will be ‘unclean’ until the evening, plus¦53951 anyone who \add ≈carries¦53951 any of those things\add*, must¦53945 wash their clothes¦53954 and bathe themself in water¦53956, and they will be ‘unclean’ until the evening.
